00:03:30.770 --> 00:03:32.020
The first Industrial
Revolution--

00:03:34.490 --> 00:03:36.330
we'll have a little quiz here.

00:03:36.330 --> 00:03:39.330
I'm going to give you
three centuries.

00:03:39.330 --> 00:03:40.440
And you can tell me when you
think the Industrial

00:03:40.440 --> 00:03:40.690
Revolution--

00:03:40.690 --> 00:03:42.820
How many people think the
Industrial Revolution happened

00:03:42.820 --> 00:03:45.290
in the 1700's?

00:03:45.290 --> 00:03:48.140
How many people thought it
happened in the 1800's?

00:03:48.140 --> 00:03:51.890
And how many people think it
happened in the 1900's?

00:03:51.890 --> 00:03:52.850
OK.

00:03:52.850 --> 00:03:56.410
The answer is 1700's, 1776.

00:03:56.410 --> 00:04:01.060
Same year as the American
Revolution was the deployment

00:04:01.060 --> 00:04:04.230
of the spinning jenny, which was
basically a spinning wheel

00:04:04.230 --> 00:04:05.980
with multiple wheels.

00:04:05.980 --> 00:04:08.550
Now we'd had spinning wheels
since fairytale times, castles

00:04:08.550 --> 00:04:10.240
and princesses and all
this kind of stuff.

00:04:10.240 --> 00:04:13.170
But what a spinning jenny did
is it used a foot treadmill

00:04:13.170 --> 00:04:15.350
and then just spun multiple
wheels at the same time and

00:04:15.350 --> 00:04:19.750
amplified human power and
basically continued the

00:04:19.750 --> 00:04:23.220
movement of moving us from
muscle power to machine power.

00:04:23.220 --> 00:04:27.350
And that was first driven by
feet, and then by water, and

00:04:27.350 --> 00:04:30.280
then by steam, and ultimately
created the factory.

00:04:30.280 --> 00:04:33.450
And so this is what
you imagined.

00:04:33.450 --> 00:04:38.530
This is a mid-1800's factory,
textile mill in England.

00:04:38.530 --> 00:04:41.270
Now this did amazing things.

00:04:41.270 --> 00:04:45.270
Not only did it turn us from
beasts of burden to more using

00:04:45.270 --> 00:04:48.310
our heads, but it also
concentrated

00:04:48.310 --> 00:04:50.050
us around the machines.

00:04:50.050 --> 00:04:51.970
Now this is a good thing
and a bad thing.

00:04:51.970 --> 00:04:54.840
It's a good thing in that it
created the city, it created

00:04:54.840 --> 00:05:00.510
urbanism and everything we now
celebrate with concentrated

00:05:00.510 --> 00:05:02.280
populations.

00:05:02.280 --> 00:05:06.170
It also vastly increased
quality of life.

00:05:06.170 --> 00:05:10.520
This is what happened to life
expectancy as the factory was

00:05:10.520 --> 00:05:12.030
created, as we moved
to cities.

00:05:12.030 --> 00:05:13.530
It doubled life expectancy.

00:05:13.530 --> 00:05:17.100
Now we think of rural England
as being pastoral and

00:05:17.100 --> 00:05:18.700
wonderful and healthy and
all this kind of stuff.

00:05:18.700 --> 00:05:21.620
But in fact, they had no access
to clean water, no

00:05:21.620 --> 00:05:24.700
sanitation systems, the walls
were damp, and no access to

00:05:24.700 --> 00:05:25.910
good health care, et cetera.

00:05:25.910 --> 00:05:29.970
What cities offered, despite
the old dark, satanic mills

00:05:29.970 --> 00:05:33.080
and all this kind of stuff, what
they actually offered was

00:05:33.080 --> 00:05:37.990
sewage systems, clean water
supplies, health care,

00:05:37.990 --> 00:05:39.870
education, all these
kind of things.

00:05:39.870 --> 00:05:44.080
And they very quickly doubled
the life expectancy.

00:05:44.080 --> 00:05:46.940
And this is what they did
to the population.

00:05:46.940 --> 00:05:51.050
That's what concentrating us
around the tools of production

00:05:51.050 --> 00:05:55.320
did to the population
of England and then

00:05:55.320 --> 00:05:56.660
the rest of the world.

00:05:56.660 --> 00:05:58.630
Now that's all good.

00:05:58.630 --> 00:06:00.080
What was bad--

00:06:00.080 --> 00:06:02.910
or not bad, but one of the
downsides of this is that,

00:06:02.910 --> 00:06:06.330
basically, it focused production
around the things

00:06:06.330 --> 00:06:08.260
that made sense for factories,
around massive

00:06:08.260 --> 00:06:09.050
economies of scale.

00:06:09.050 --> 00:06:11.300
So the things that got made
were the things that were

00:06:11.300 --> 00:06:13.110
mass-produced.

00:06:13.110 --> 00:06:15.500
Now that's great, if you
want cheaper spoons.

00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:17.790
But it really limits
choice and variety.

00:06:17.790 --> 00:06:22.940
And so we ended up with that
sort of Marxian construct of

00:06:22.940 --> 00:06:25.120
power going to those who
control the means of

00:06:25.120 --> 00:06:29.470
production and the man deciding
what gets made.

00:06:29.470 --> 00:06:32.580
You just couldn't beat those
economies of scale.

00:06:32.580 --> 00:06:35.300
Now that is, again,
no bad thing.

00:06:35.300 --> 00:06:37.900
It improved quality of life
and gave access to

00:06:37.900 --> 00:06:42.250
high-quality goods to everybody
or to many people.

00:06:42.250 --> 00:06:45.820
But we did destroy the
cottage industry.

00:06:45.820 --> 00:06:49.490
We did destroy craftsmanship,
artisanal construction.

00:06:49.490 --> 00:06:53.560
And ultimately we ended up, as
that trend towards cheaper

00:06:53.560 --> 00:06:57.200
labor continued, eliminating
many manufacturing jobs

00:06:57.200 --> 00:07:00.170
outside of Asia.

00:07:00.170 --> 00:07:01.630
That was the first Industrial
Revolution.

00:07:01.630 --> 00:07:06.320
That took us from about 1776
to mid-20th century.

00:07:06.320 --> 00:07:09.100
Then came, what we could call,
the second Industrial

00:07:09.100 --> 00:07:11.470
Revolution, which is the
Digital Revolution.

00:07:11.470 --> 00:07:13.800
Now I'm not showing
the mainframe.

00:07:13.800 --> 00:07:15.760
And I'm not even showing
a personal computer.

00:07:15.760 --> 00:07:20.670
Instead, I'm using a different
construct here, which is

00:07:20.670 --> 00:07:22.726
called publishing,
if you will.

00:07:22.726 --> 00:07:25.910
What I'm showing here is the
first laser printer, the Apple

00:07:25.910 --> 00:07:27.670
LaserWriter from 1985.

00:07:27.670 --> 00:07:32.830
It came out one year after the
Mac and cost about $2,500.

00:07:32.830 --> 00:07:35.090
Now that created desktop
publishing.

00:07:35.090 --> 00:07:36.890
And today, we think nothing
of desktop publishing.

00:07:36.890 --> 00:07:40.400
But when that came out, these
more mind blowing words,

00:07:40.400 --> 00:07:41.685
desktop publishing.

00:07:41.685 --> 00:07:46.030
Now publishing was
a factory job.

00:07:46.030 --> 00:07:49.460
To publish, you had to buy ink
by the barrel, buy paper by

00:07:49.460 --> 00:07:51.450
the railway car.

00:07:51.450 --> 00:07:54.170
You needed to have a printing
plant to publish.

00:07:54.170 --> 00:07:56.450
And now you could do
the same quality

00:07:56.450 --> 00:07:58.760
production on your desktop.

00:07:58.760 --> 00:07:59.430
That's good.

00:07:59.430 --> 00:08:01.200
That's impressive.

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:04.700
Hundreds of years of
professional skills and

00:08:04.700 --> 00:08:07.280
publishing were turned into
a bit of software

00:08:07.280 --> 00:08:08.650
and a button press.

00:08:08.650 --> 00:08:12.410
But you couldn't really be
a publisher, because you

00:08:12.410 --> 00:08:14.280
couldn't distribute.

00:08:14.280 --> 00:08:17.160
You could make church
newsletters and missing cat

00:08:17.160 --> 00:08:18.870
posters, but you couldn't
make millions and

00:08:18.870 --> 00:08:19.820
get them out there.

00:08:19.820 --> 00:08:21.660
And then, along came the web.

00:08:21.660 --> 00:08:24.890
And "publish" turned into
a button that you

00:08:24.890 --> 00:08:25.840
click on the screen.

00:08:25.840 --> 00:08:28.470
And every time you press the
Publish button, whether it's

00:08:28.470 --> 00:08:31.090
on your blog or whatever, you
don't think about it, but

00:08:31.090 --> 00:08:36.270
you've basically turned what
used to be a industry run by

00:08:36.270 --> 00:08:38.539
factories and professionals,
and you've turned it into a

00:08:38.539 --> 00:08:39.730
single click.

00:08:39.730 --> 00:08:42.870
But that act of democratizing
the tools of prototyping and

00:08:42.870 --> 00:08:46.840
then the tools of distribution
basically took the publishing

00:08:46.840 --> 00:08:48.370
industry and opened it
up to everybody.

00:08:48.370 --> 00:08:50.160
And we know what happened.

00:08:50.160 --> 00:08:52.110
That was the web and
the long tail.

00:08:52.110 --> 00:08:54.480
And it changed the world.

00:08:54.480 --> 00:08:56.640
OK, but you take those
two analogies

00:08:56.640 --> 00:08:59.930
and now fast forward.

00:08:59.930 --> 00:09:04.080
Rather than the laser printer,
we have the 3D printer.

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:07.240
This is the new Replicator
2 from MakerBot.

00:09:07.240 --> 00:09:11.230
And it does the same thing as
a laser printer, which is to

00:09:11.230 --> 00:09:12.910
say it takes bits on
the screen and

00:09:12.910 --> 00:09:13.860
turns them into atoms.

00:09:13.860 --> 00:09:17.040
Now a 2D printer takes bits on
the screen in turns them to

00:09:17.040 --> 00:09:18.530
ink or toner or things
like that.

00:09:18.530 --> 00:09:22.440
A 3D printer takes images,
polygons, designs on the

00:09:22.440 --> 00:09:26.840
screen, and turns it into a
physical object that's built

00:09:26.840 --> 00:09:30.400
up in layers of plastic
or other materials.

00:09:30.400 --> 00:09:32.150
But once again, it
takes all the

00:09:32.150 --> 00:09:33.890
complexity out of the process.

00:09:33.890 --> 00:09:35.060
You don't need to know anything

00:09:35.060 --> 00:09:36.710
about plastic or machining.

00:09:36.710 --> 00:09:38.860
You just press a button and,
poof, out it comes.

00:09:38.860 --> 00:09:40.690
OK, that's great for
making one or

00:09:40.690 --> 00:09:41.980
two or three of something.

00:09:41.980 --> 00:09:42.990
It's great for prototyping.

00:09:42.990 --> 00:09:45.600
They call rapid prototyping.

00:09:45.600 --> 00:09:46.910
But that doesn't make
you a manufacturer.

00:09:46.910 --> 00:09:48.670
That doesn't make
you a factory.

00:09:48.670 --> 00:09:51.660
The next step is actually less
understood, but probably more

00:09:51.660 --> 00:09:56.090
exciting, and that is basically
cloud manufacturing.

00:09:56.090 --> 00:09:58.590
The world's supply chains are
now impedance matched to the

00:09:58.590 --> 00:09:59.660
individual.

