And it turns out that, although
they would sell me

00:11:36.730 --> 00:11:38.585
motors wholesale, they actually
said, you know, it's

00:11:38.585 --> 00:11:40.260
just as easy for us to custom
make them for you.

00:11:40.260 --> 00:11:41.380
What specs would you like?

00:11:41.380 --> 00:11:42.050
Shaft length?

00:11:42.050 --> 00:11:42.690
Windings?

00:11:42.690 --> 00:11:43.660
Motors?

00:11:43.660 --> 00:11:44.260
Voltages?

00:11:44.260 --> 00:11:46.230
And I was like, I don't
really know.

00:11:46.230 --> 00:11:49.080
But they walked me through it
with a form I could fill out.

00:11:49.080 --> 00:11:50.790
And then we did it.

00:11:50.790 --> 00:11:53.820
And then I gave them my
credit card number.

00:11:53.820 --> 00:11:58.530
And 10 days later, I got a box
of 1,000 motors with that

00:11:58.530 --> 00:12:00.210
little greasy sheen, because
they'd just come out of the

00:12:00.210 --> 00:12:02.845
factory and this foam
layer between them

00:12:02.845 --> 00:12:03.770
with all these little--

00:12:03.770 --> 00:12:05.330
it was all perfectly made
in a layer of plastic.

00:12:05.330 --> 00:12:06.500
And I was like, oh my god!

00:12:06.500 --> 00:12:08.330
I just got a factory
in China--

00:12:08.330 --> 00:12:10.770
I got robots in China
to work for me.

00:12:10.770 --> 00:12:13.820
And I didn't need anything
more than a credit card.

00:12:13.820 --> 00:12:15.290
Now this may not seem like
a big deal to you.

00:12:15.290 --> 00:12:17.690
But I used to live in China, and
I can tell you it didn't

00:12:17.690 --> 00:12:19.520
used to be like that.

00:12:19.520 --> 00:12:22.190
If you wanted a factory in China
to work for you, you had

00:12:22.190 --> 00:12:23.610
to fly to Hong Kong.

00:12:23.610 --> 00:12:26.930
You had to use a facilitator
or a finder to make an

00:12:26.930 --> 00:12:29.180
introduction to a factory.

00:12:29.180 --> 00:12:32.560
Much trust or lack thereof
went on there.

00:12:32.560 --> 00:12:33.580
You then went across
the border.

00:12:33.580 --> 00:12:34.230
You got that introduction.

00:12:34.230 --> 00:12:35.760
You had a very awkward
meeting.

00:12:35.760 --> 00:12:37.380
This involved then going
to dinner together.

00:12:37.380 --> 00:12:41.380
You had eat fish eyeballs, kind
of a hazing ritual thing.

00:12:41.380 --> 00:12:44.770
And then more drinking,
karaoke.

00:12:44.770 --> 00:12:45.470
And this went on.

00:12:45.470 --> 00:12:46.790
And then you had to get
a letter of credit.

00:12:46.790 --> 00:12:47.960
And then a bank transfer.

00:12:47.960 --> 00:12:51.170
And then like six months later,
after much negotiation,

00:12:51.170 --> 00:12:52.950
you might get your samples.

00:12:52.950 --> 00:12:55.010
And you had to be a company,
by the way.

00:12:55.010 --> 00:12:57.950
And I had just done it in 20
minutes with a credit card.

00:12:57.950 --> 00:12:59.370
And I'm just a guy.

00:12:59.370 --> 00:13:03.230
And at that moment, I realized
that the world's supply chains

00:13:03.230 --> 00:13:04.940
had opened up to
the individual.

00:13:04.940 --> 00:13:07.470
And it's only gotten
better since then.

00:13:07.470 --> 00:13:10.620
So now we have this way.

00:13:10.620 --> 00:13:12.770
What the Maker Movement
represents, what this part of

00:13:12.770 --> 00:13:15.920
the Maker Movement represents is
the web generation getting

00:13:15.920 --> 00:13:17.100
to physical stuff.

00:13:17.100 --> 00:13:20.100
And what that means is the
designs start on-screen.

00:13:20.100 --> 00:13:23.800
They start with a digital
design, a CAD file, typically.

00:13:23.800 --> 00:13:25.550
And it could be electronics.

00:13:25.550 --> 00:13:27.140
It could be physical.

00:13:27.140 --> 00:13:31.720
And you can print locally on
your 3D printer or laser

00:13:31.720 --> 00:13:32.810
cutter or CNC.

00:13:32.810 --> 00:13:35.370
Or you can print globally
by just uploading to

00:13:35.370 --> 00:13:36.120
one of these services.

00:13:36.120 --> 00:13:38.260
And the machines speak
the same language.

00:13:38.260 --> 00:13:40.600
In the desktop publishing
era, it was PostScript.

00:13:40.600 --> 00:13:42.590
So the machine on your desktop
spoke the same language as the

00:13:42.590 --> 00:13:43.510
biggest printers in the world.

00:13:43.510 --> 00:13:44.580
And now it's things
like [? Chico ?]

00:13:44.580 --> 00:13:45.910
[? with their STLs. ?]

00:13:45.910 --> 00:13:48.470
It's the same language,
scale agnostic.

00:13:48.470 --> 00:13:51.440
So we now have a scale-free
manufacturing system.

00:13:51.440 --> 00:13:54.000
And that is the enabling
technology of the

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:56.550
long tail of stuff.

00:13:56.550 --> 00:14:00.730
OK, this is what I suddenly
realized when that

00:14:00.730 --> 00:14:01.330
first box showed up.

00:14:01.330 --> 00:14:05.440
I was like, oh my god!

00:14:05.440 --> 00:14:06.600
I was meant to do this.

00:14:06.600 --> 00:14:08.500
This is my grandfather.

00:14:08.500 --> 00:14:09.850
His name is Fred Hauser.

00:14:09.850 --> 00:14:11.640
I hadn't forgot about my
grandfather, but I'd forgotten

00:14:11.640 --> 00:14:15.040
about this element of him
until this happened.

00:14:15.040 --> 00:14:19.190
Fred Hauser was a Swiss engineer
who immigrated to Los

00:14:19.190 --> 00:14:24.130
Angeles in the late 1920s
and worked in Hollywood.

00:14:24.130 --> 00:14:25.150
Hollywood was a very mechanical

00:14:25.150 --> 00:14:27.030
business in those days.

00:14:27.030 --> 00:14:29.280
The film transport,
lots of gears.

00:14:29.280 --> 00:14:31.330
The audio was lots of
gears and pulleys

00:14:31.330 --> 00:14:31.930
and things like that.

00:14:31.930 --> 00:14:36.830
And so it was a place for a
Swiss engineer good at gears.

00:14:36.830 --> 00:14:39.260
But at night he was
an inventor.

00:14:39.260 --> 00:14:42.380
And this is what he
invented, the

00:14:42.380 --> 00:14:43.800
automatic sprinkler system.

00:14:43.800 --> 00:14:46.150
So if you have an automatic
sprinkler system, you have my

00:14:46.150 --> 00:14:47.010
grandfather to thank.

00:14:47.010 --> 00:14:49.410
By the way, this is exactly what
a Swiss engineer would

00:14:49.410 --> 00:14:51.210
invent if you put him in LA.

00:14:51.210 --> 00:14:55.560
So LA is greening the deserts
with a sprinkler system.

00:14:55.560 --> 00:14:57.020
And then the problem
is but you had to

00:14:57.020 --> 00:14:57.940
turn them on and off.

00:14:57.940 --> 00:15:00.400
And a Swiss engineer would just
put a watch on top of a

00:15:00.400 --> 00:15:01.690
sprinkler systems.

00:15:01.690 --> 00:15:03.670
And you know those dials
with the little pins

00:15:03.670 --> 00:15:04.550
that you put in?

00:15:04.550 --> 00:15:06.610
That's what he invented.

00:15:06.610 --> 00:15:07.770
So cool.

00:15:07.770 --> 00:15:09.980
That was great.

00:15:09.980 --> 00:15:10.910
This was not so great.

00:15:10.910 --> 00:15:13.220
This is what you had to
do to get into market.

00:15:13.220 --> 00:15:14.510
You had a patent it.

00:15:14.510 --> 00:15:15.640
And he hated patenting.

00:15:15.640 --> 00:15:16.340
It was expensive.

00:15:16.340 --> 00:15:17.220
He hated working with lawyers.

00:15:17.220 --> 00:15:18.440
It took forever.

00:15:18.440 --> 00:15:21.430
But after you patented it,
you could license it to a

00:15:21.430 --> 00:15:22.550
manufacturer.

00:15:22.550 --> 00:15:25.910
And this is what was made, the
Moody Rain Master, which

00:15:25.910 --> 00:15:29.120
allowed you to hang out at the
beach while your garden

00:15:29.120 --> 00:15:31.130
watered itself.

00:15:31.130 --> 00:15:34.030
And this is a huge
success, right?

00:15:34.030 --> 00:15:36.950
This is a great victory of
20th century invention.

00:15:36.950 --> 00:15:39.970
His invention actually
made it to market.

00:15:39.970 --> 00:15:41.990
He made some money.

00:15:41.990 --> 00:15:42.670
This is good.

00:15:42.670 --> 00:15:44.720
Almost nobody got this far.

00:15:44.720 --> 00:15:48.460
But it's also a little tragic
in that he was an inventor,

00:15:48.460 --> 00:15:50.510
but he wasn't an entrepreneur.

00:15:50.510 --> 00:15:52.860
He never left his workshop.

00:15:52.860 --> 00:15:54.430
He lost control of
his invention.

00:15:54.430 --> 00:15:55.770
And it got made by
this company.

00:15:55.770 --> 00:15:57.500
And they changed it.

00:15:57.500 --> 00:15:59.490
And they kind of forgot
about him.

00:15:59.490 --> 00:16:03.010
And I remember in the late
1970s, when I'd go visit him,

00:16:03.010 --> 00:16:05.610
we went to see the factory.

00:16:05.610 --> 00:16:08.350
He was proud that his product
was being made.

00:16:08.350 --> 00:16:10.780
And it was clear they couldn't
quite remember who he was and

00:16:10.780 --> 00:16:11.470
why he was there.

00:16:11.470 --> 00:16:13.740
And somebody finally reminded
them that this was Mr. Hauser

00:16:13.740 --> 00:16:15.240
who had invented the
sprinkler system.

00:16:15.240 --> 00:16:16.310
And they were all very polite.

00:16:16.310 --> 00:16:18.470
But it was clear they didn't
need him, they didn't want him

00:16:18.470 --> 00:16:24.020
there, and that, once his
invention was done, that they

00:16:24.020 --> 00:16:25.870
would take it from there.

00:16:25.870 --> 00:16:27.990
Those who owned the factories,
those who owned the means of

00:16:27.990 --> 00:16:31.970
production still controlled
the product.

00:16:31.970 --> 00:16:33.590
I spent my summers with him.

00:16:33.590 --> 00:16:36.220
And he taught me how to do
mechanical drawing, which I've

00:16:36.220 --> 00:16:38.440
entirely forgotten
at this point.

00:16:38.440 --> 00:16:40.200
And then he taught me-- this
was kind of magical--

00:16:40.200 --> 00:16:43.530
how to use a metal lathe
in a machine tool shop.

00:16:43.530 --> 00:16:45.040
One summer--

00:16:45.040 --> 00:16:47.060
I think I was 12 this summer--

00:16:47.060 --> 00:16:49.380
he said, this summer we're going
to make an engine, an

00:16:49.380 --> 00:16:50.780
internal combustion engine.

00:16:50.780 --> 00:16:51.500
And I was like, cool!

00:16:51.500 --> 00:16:53.630
And he says, I've
ordered a kit.

00:16:53.630 --> 00:16:56.200
So I show up and there's a
box there, sure enough.

00:16:56.200 --> 00:16:57.540
And I knew what kits were.

00:16:57.540 --> 00:16:58.530
I'd built model airplanes.

00:16:58.530 --> 00:17:01.850
There were lots of plastic
parts and numbers and

00:17:01.850 --> 00:17:02.770
instructions et cetera.

00:17:02.770 --> 00:17:04.040
And we opened the box.

00:17:04.040 --> 00:17:07.250
And there's these four blocks
of metal and a blueprint.

00:17:07.250 --> 00:17:09.520
And I'm like, grandpa,
where's the engine?

00:17:09.520 --> 00:17:13.030
And he's like, it's in there,
and we have to get it out.

00:17:13.030 --> 00:17:13.859
And we did.

00:17:13.859 --> 00:17:14.609
We did.

00:17:14.609 --> 00:17:17.060
What a skilled machinist can do
is take blocks of metal and

00:17:17.060 --> 00:17:18.050
put them on metal lathes.

00:17:18.050 --> 00:17:20.890
And curly-cues build up around
your feet, just like a

00:17:20.890 --> 00:17:22.520
sculptor cutting away
the bit of marble

00:17:22.520 --> 00:17:24.089
that isn't the figure.

00:17:24.089 --> 00:17:25.869
It's absolutely spectacular
and magical.

00:17:25.869 --> 00:17:29.680
And you can see that you could
make anything, if you have

00:17:29.680 --> 00:17:30.880
those skills.

00:17:30.880 --> 00:17:33.820
My grandfather was not just an
inventor, he was a machinist.

00:17:33.820 --> 00:17:35.420
And you need to be a machinist
to take your

00:17:35.420 --> 00:17:37.120
idea and make it real.

00:17:37.120 --> 00:17:39.570
And so I realized at that point,
as I was looking at

00:17:39.570 --> 00:17:42.000
this box full of motors that
showed up from China, and like

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:42.950
I made that.

00:17:42.950 --> 00:17:44.330
Oh my god.

00:17:44.330 --> 00:17:45.940
I can't believe I can do that.

00:17:45.940 --> 00:17:48.590
Why had I forgotten that I'd
spent my summers with grandpa

00:17:48.590 --> 00:17:49.330
making stuff?

00:17:49.330 --> 00:17:50.910
And I realized it's because
I'm not a machinist.

00:17:50.910 --> 00:17:51.740
I didn't have those skills.

00:17:51.740 --> 00:17:56.060
And I had no way to get my
ideas real, until now.

00:17:56.060 --> 00:17:57.780
So when you get a 3D printer--

00:17:57.780 --> 00:18:00.570
and my homework assignment for
any of you who have children,

00:18:00.570 --> 00:18:03.180
but maybe even those that
don't, is get one--

00:18:03.180 --> 00:18:04.000
it's mind blowing.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:06.940
But when you get a 3D printer
or a CNC machine or a laser

00:18:06.940 --> 00:18:10.100
cutter or just want to use
these services, all those

00:18:10.100 --> 00:18:13.620
skills that you used to
need to have go away.

00:18:13.620 --> 00:18:14.060
They're abstracted.

00:18:14.060 --> 00:18:15.790
The software handles that.

00:18:15.790 --> 00:18:20.040
And that barrier to entry of
making things real has

00:18:20.040 --> 00:18:23.000
disappeared in the same way that
that Publish button on

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:25.980
Blogger et cetera took away
that barrier of entry of

00:18:25.980 --> 00:18:28.030
having to own a printing
plant and understand

00:18:28.030 --> 00:18:29.250
the publishing industry.

00:18:29.250 --> 00:18:32.440
That is the magical thing here
is that, suddenly, there's

00:18:32.440 --> 00:18:36.030
nothing standing between
ideas and practice.

00:18:36.030 --> 00:18:41.000
And that step, right
now, is optional.

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:42.970
There's a movie that came out
a few years ago called, "A

00:18:42.970 --> 00:18:45.870
Flash of Genius," that was kind
of a warning to those who

00:18:45.870 --> 00:18:48.360
would pursue invention
in the 20th century.

00:18:48.360 --> 00:18:50.600
This is about the invention of
the intermittent windshield

00:18:50.600 --> 00:18:53.160
wiper, which is basically the
windshield wipers that pause

00:18:53.160 --> 00:18:54.100
when it's not raining
very hard.

00:18:54.100 --> 00:18:55.750
It's just a little
timer circuit.

00:18:55.750 --> 00:18:57.310
And there's a picture
from the movie.

00:18:57.310 --> 00:18:58.620
This is a guy, same
deal, just like my

00:18:58.620 --> 00:19:00.350
grandfather, in his basement.

00:19:00.350 --> 00:19:01.520
Comes up with the invention.

00:19:01.520 --> 00:19:03.490
He too patents it.

00:19:03.490 --> 00:19:06.660
But rather than license it, he
decides that he wants to be an

00:19:06.660 --> 00:19:07.400
entrepreneur.

00:19:07.400 --> 00:19:08.750
He decides he wants
to make it too.

00:19:08.750 --> 00:19:11.910
He wants to control his
invention, understandably.

00:19:11.910 --> 00:19:13.130
Unfortunately, it was
really hard in those

00:19:13.130 --> 00:19:13.980
days to make factories.

00:19:13.980 --> 00:19:15.580
So he mortgages his house.

00:19:15.580 --> 00:19:16.530
And he starts building
a factory.

00:19:16.530 --> 00:19:18.110
He rents some space.

00:19:18.110 --> 00:19:20.630
Assembly lines come
in, forklifts.

00:19:20.630 --> 00:19:24.580
1961, '62, '63, he's
still not finished.

00:19:24.580 --> 00:19:28.250
And in the movie, they portray
the scene where he's at 1964.

00:19:28.250 --> 00:19:30.460
He's leaving his still
unfinished factory.

00:19:30.460 --> 00:19:31.770
It's raining.

00:19:31.770 --> 00:19:32.650
He's a little dejected.

00:19:32.650 --> 00:19:33.790
He turns the corner.

00:19:33.790 --> 00:19:37.520
And the new 1965 Mustangs are
turning the corner to be

00:19:37.520 --> 00:19:39.430
unveiled for the first time.

00:19:39.430 --> 00:19:42.050
And their windshield
wipers are pausing.

00:19:42.050 --> 00:19:44.660
And he realizes that his
idea has been stolen.

00:19:44.660 --> 00:19:45.880
And he's ruined.

00:19:45.880 --> 00:19:48.840
And his descent into
madness then fuels

00:19:48.840 --> 00:19:49.690
the rest of the film.

00:19:49.690 --> 00:19:50.690
And it's all very
entertaining.

00:19:50.690 --> 00:19:54.830
But the message was,
don't dare do that.

00:19:54.830 --> 00:19:56.690
Don't be an entrepreneur
in the physical space.

00:19:56.690 --> 00:19:57.870
It's too hard.

00:19:57.870 --> 00:19:58.690
You need a factory.

00:19:58.690 --> 00:20:00.680
And factories are not for you.

00:20:00.680 --> 00:20:02.990
So that's the way
it used to be.

00:20:02.990 --> 00:20:04.850
And this is the way it is now.

00:20:04.850 --> 00:20:06.050
Many of you may recognize
this.

00:20:06.050 --> 00:20:08.120
This is TechShop, just
down the road.

00:20:08.120 --> 00:20:10.070
This is the new factory.

00:20:10.070 --> 00:20:12.780
What you have here is
basically the gym.

00:20:12.780 --> 00:20:16.110
In the same way that a gym is
a place where, for a monthly

00:20:16.110 --> 00:20:18.010
subscription fee, you get
access to machinery you

00:20:18.010 --> 00:20:20.990
couldn't afford or wouldn't want
in your house, training,

00:20:20.990 --> 00:20:24.340
other people who are doing the
same thing as an inspiration,

00:20:24.340 --> 00:20:26.640
this is that for
manufacturing.

00:20:26.640 --> 00:20:29.930
You have access to 3D printers,
CNCs, laser cutters,

00:20:29.930 --> 00:20:32.250
software tools, traditional
machining tools, all

00:20:32.250 --> 00:20:33.030
this kind of stuff.

00:20:33.030 --> 00:20:34.370
They have trainers.

00:20:34.370 --> 00:20:35.440
They have classes.

00:20:35.440 --> 00:20:36.990
They have other people doing
inspiring things.

00:20:36.990 --> 00:20:38.576
The guy here on the front is--

00:20:38.576 --> 00:20:42.660
I don't know whether my laser
pointer here works--

00:20:42.660 --> 00:20:47.660
the guy here in the front here
is doing the wireless control

00:20:47.660 --> 00:20:50.070
module for the smart grid.

00:20:50.070 --> 00:20:53.900
The guy right there is doing a
vapor deposition chamber for

00:20:53.900 --> 00:20:55.240
synthetic diamonds.

00:20:55.240 --> 00:20:56.920
In the back, they're building
a lunar lander

00:20:56.920 --> 00:20:59.520
because, why not?

00:20:59.520 --> 00:21:02.650
And what's great is, because
they start on screen as

00:21:02.650 --> 00:21:05.420
digital files, they then do
some prototypes here.

00:21:05.420 --> 00:21:08.370
And then they upload them to
the cloud, more or less.

00:21:08.370 --> 00:21:10.140
And they can be manufactured
at any scale.

00:21:10.140 --> 00:21:12.350
This guy, interestingly, his
wireless control modules, when

00:21:12.350 --> 00:21:15.780
he's done with them, they say
ABB, which is a big Swedish

00:21:15.780 --> 00:21:16.990
engineering firm, on them.

00:21:16.990 --> 00:21:18.230
You probably think they're
made in a big Swedish

00:21:18.230 --> 00:21:19.990
engineering factory,
but they're not.

00:21:19.990 --> 00:21:25.370
They're made in small batches
by this guy and his team and

00:21:25.370 --> 00:21:26.770
simply distributed by ABB.

00:21:26.770 --> 00:21:30.670
But that's the power
of this model.

00:21:30.670 --> 00:21:33.470
Because these designs start
digital, and because the tools

00:21:33.470 --> 00:21:36.570
necessary to make them real are
so easy and accessible,

00:21:36.570 --> 00:21:39.360
that you get this kind
of long tail effect.

00:21:39.360 --> 00:21:41.870
You get this explosion of
entrepreneurship and

00:21:41.870 --> 00:21:46.150
innovation happening in
using the web model.

00:21:46.150 --> 00:21:50.990
This is a map of the current
spread of maker spaces or

00:21:50.990 --> 00:21:52.750
hacker spaces.

00:21:52.750 --> 00:21:54.490
A TechShop is a kind of
commercial chain.

00:21:54.490 --> 00:21:57.210
Actually, interestingly, the guy
who runs TechShop used to

00:21:57.210 --> 00:21:58.230
run Kinko's.

00:21:58.230 --> 00:22:01.590
And if you think of it, Kinko's
was the publishing

00:22:01.590 --> 00:22:04.150
industry turned into a

00:22:04.150 --> 00:22:06.380
regionally distributed service.

00:22:06.380 --> 00:22:08.340
And TechShop is the
manufacturing industry turned

00:22:08.340 --> 00:22:10.070
into a regionally distributed
service.

00:22:10.070 --> 00:22:12.080
And these maker spaces are
the same sort of thing.

00:22:12.080 --> 00:22:13.910
They're places where you can go,
if you don't want to own

00:22:13.910 --> 00:22:16.920
your own 3D printer, laser
cutter, you can just have

00:22:16.920 --> 00:22:19.500
access to one in a shared
environment.

00:22:19.500 --> 00:22:20.600
So these are spreading
everywhere.

00:22:20.600 --> 00:22:23.450
And this is very exciting that
it's not all clustered in the

00:22:23.450 --> 00:22:24.100
United States.

00:22:24.100 --> 00:22:25.130
It can really happen anywhere.

00:22:25.130 --> 00:22:27.220
And things like the Fab Labs
that came out of MIT are a

00:22:27.220 --> 00:22:28.470
good example of this as well.

00:22:31.220 --> 00:22:32.900
The funding model, of course,
is Kickstarter.

00:22:32.900 --> 00:22:34.930
I don't really need to tell you
more about Kickstarter and

00:22:34.930 --> 00:22:37.480
Pebble being one of the most
successful projects.

00:22:37.480 --> 00:22:40.710
But basically, it does
three magical things.

00:22:40.710 --> 00:22:42.690
The first magical thing
Kickstarter does is it moves

00:22:42.690 --> 00:22:44.600
money forward in time.

00:22:44.600 --> 00:22:48.350
When you think about it, the
traditional method of

00:22:48.350 --> 00:22:50.940
manufacturing has got that whole
monetary flow all wrong,

00:22:50.940 --> 00:22:53.440
which is, basically, you pay a
lot of money up front to do

00:22:53.440 --> 00:22:57.010
your R&amp;D and your prototyping
and your tooling.

00:22:57.010 --> 00:22:59.320
And then you have to assemble
your components and inventory

00:22:59.320 --> 00:22:59.820
your components.

00:22:59.820 --> 00:23:01.950
Then you have to build
the devices.

00:23:01.950 --> 00:23:03.440
Then you have to
warehouse them.

00:23:03.440 --> 00:23:05.550
Then you have to put them into
the distribution channel.

00:23:05.550 --> 00:23:07.100
Then they sell.

00:23:07.100 --> 00:23:07.990
Then they go through this.

00:23:07.990 --> 00:23:09.370
Then the money comes in.

00:23:09.370 --> 00:23:11.740
Most of it gets taken away
by third-parties.

00:23:11.740 --> 00:23:12.950
And then you get paid.

00:23:12.950 --> 00:23:14.990
So you have to spend all
your money at the

00:23:14.990 --> 00:23:15.880
front end of the process.

00:23:15.880 --> 00:23:18.550
And you get some of it at the
back end of the process.

00:23:18.550 --> 00:23:21.220
And by simply taking pre-orders,
they move the

00:23:21.220 --> 00:23:23.870
money forward in time
to when you need it.

00:23:23.870 --> 00:23:24.260
So that's great.

00:23:24.260 --> 00:23:25.230
That's one thing.

00:23:25.230 --> 00:23:27.820
Number two is market research.

00:23:27.820 --> 00:23:29.950
As you know, you have to pass
your goal to get approved.

00:23:29.950 --> 00:23:31.860
Now, in this case, the
goal was 100,000.

00:23:31.860 --> 00:23:33.780
The kind of blew through
that one.

00:23:33.780 --> 00:23:38.290
But if they hadn't, that
would have been a gift.

00:23:38.290 --> 00:23:40.780
If you don't hit your goal,
that tells you the product

00:23:40.780 --> 00:23:41.780
probably would not have sold.

00:23:41.780 --> 00:23:43.490
And you just saved yourself
a ton of time

00:23:43.490 --> 00:23:45.130
and money right there.

00:23:45.130 --> 00:23:47.780
So free market research
is golden.

00:23:47.780 --> 00:23:48.820
And number three--

00:23:48.820 --> 00:23:52.245
and this is the most important
thing, I think--

00:23:52.245 --> 00:23:54.000
is that it builds a community.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:57.110
And this is a community
of customers,

00:23:57.110 --> 00:23:58.270
but not just customers.

00:23:58.270 --> 00:24:00.240
They're also co-participants
in the

00:24:00.240 --> 00:24:01.550
product development itself.

00:24:01.550 --> 00:24:03.650
So if that was you that followed
the Pebble watch--

