00:31:40.080 --> 00:31:43.110
uploaded the most beautiful
dollhouse furniture designs

00:31:43.110 --> 00:31:44.220
for free on Thingiverse.

00:31:44.220 --> 00:31:46.490
And we found a chair that
was just right.

00:31:46.490 --> 00:31:48.920
And then we printed it out.

00:31:48.920 --> 00:31:51.030
And then the four-year-old
painted it.

00:31:51.030 --> 00:31:54.440
And they love their dollhouse
furniture now.

00:31:54.440 --> 00:31:56.840
So if you're a toy company,
this should

00:31:56.840 --> 00:31:59.680
fill you with terror.

00:31:59.680 --> 00:32:02.910
We basically did
this for free.

00:32:02.910 --> 00:32:04.060
The kids were super engaged.

00:32:04.060 --> 00:32:06.060
They got exactly what they
wanted and, by the way, at

00:32:06.060 --> 00:32:07.200
exactly the right size.

00:32:07.200 --> 00:32:08.890
There's little sliders,
so you scale so it's

00:32:08.890 --> 00:32:09.990
just the right size.

00:32:09.990 --> 00:32:11.930
Then they made it their
own with the painting.

00:32:11.930 --> 00:32:12.990
And they love this stuff.

00:32:12.990 --> 00:32:13.750
They treasure it.

00:32:13.750 --> 00:32:15.370
They actually take the doll's
furniture out of the dollhouse

00:32:15.370 --> 00:32:17.930
and they put it on their window
sill, because they're

00:32:17.930 --> 00:32:19.250
so proud of their dollhouse
furniture.

00:32:19.250 --> 00:32:22.870
They don't feel that way about
stuff they buy at Walmart.

00:32:22.870 --> 00:32:25.130
So is it better than the stuff
they buy in the Walmart?

00:32:25.130 --> 00:32:25.800
No.

00:32:25.800 --> 00:32:27.620
But it's righter for my kids.

00:32:27.620 --> 00:32:29.760
And there's something
of them in it.

00:32:29.760 --> 00:32:32.100
In the same way that buying
something from Kickstarter,

00:32:32.100 --> 00:32:33.280
there's a little something
of you in it.

00:32:33.280 --> 00:32:34.830
You care more about it than
you did from something you

00:32:34.830 --> 00:32:35.640
bought in a store.

00:32:35.640 --> 00:32:39.660
It's something that you 3D
printed and then maybe painted

00:32:39.660 --> 00:32:42.500
or customized.

00:32:42.500 --> 00:32:43.740
There's a connection
you have there.

00:32:43.740 --> 00:32:46.280
You value this more than
something that's

00:32:46.280 --> 00:32:47.950
mass-produced.

00:32:47.950 --> 00:32:49.820
We've seen this before
in music, right?

00:32:49.820 --> 00:32:51.100
The best music is
the stuff that

00:32:51.100 --> 00:32:52.810
everybody else isn't into.

00:32:52.810 --> 00:32:55.720
That's the story of the long
tail is that appealing to your

00:32:55.720 --> 00:32:59.660
individual needs, appealing to
what defines you as a person

00:32:59.660 --> 00:33:01.640
makes you value things more.

00:33:01.640 --> 00:33:06.340
Artisanal food, we get it.

00:33:06.340 --> 00:33:07.860
We're past one-size-fits-all.

00:33:07.860 --> 00:33:12.400
And this is very much a
one-size-fits-one approach to

00:33:12.400 --> 00:33:13.830
dollhouse furniture.

00:33:13.830 --> 00:33:18.870
My boys, needless to say, are
into Warhammer 40K mechs.

00:33:18.870 --> 00:33:21.995
Same deal, download the design,
print it out, paint

00:33:21.995 --> 00:33:23.245
it, customize it.

00:33:25.690 --> 00:33:28.650
Not as good as an official
Warhammer 40K mech, but

00:33:28.650 --> 00:33:30.720
exactly what they want.

00:33:30.720 --> 00:33:32.610
Now that's just in our house.

00:33:32.610 --> 00:33:35.070
I don't know what the killer
app for 3D printers is.

00:33:35.070 --> 00:33:38.970
But I do know that, when you
give a kid a 3D printer and

00:33:38.970 --> 00:33:40.830
they have access to Thingiverse
and easy tools to

00:33:40.830 --> 00:33:45.590
customize, that the imagination
runs riot.

00:33:45.590 --> 00:33:47.790
And what these kids know is
that anything they could

00:33:47.790 --> 00:33:48.840
imagine they can make real.

00:33:48.840 --> 00:33:51.560
Right now, they can make it real
in plastic in one color.

00:33:51.560 --> 00:33:53.380
Soon it'll be plastic
and multicolors.

00:33:53.380 --> 00:33:56.300
Soon it will be much
higher resolution.

00:33:56.300 --> 00:33:57.550
Soon it'll be multi-material.

00:33:57.550 --> 00:33:59.330
Then they'll be able
to integrate the

00:33:59.330 --> 00:34:01.130
electronics into it.

00:34:01.130 --> 00:34:02.370
They'll be able to
print in metal.

00:34:02.370 --> 00:34:04.060
We can see the way
this is going.

00:34:04.060 --> 00:34:07.480
It's not going to take 20 years
to get professional

00:34:07.480 --> 00:34:11.420
quality manufacturing
on your desktop.

00:34:11.420 --> 00:34:12.739
We've been in the dot
matrix period.

00:34:12.739 --> 00:34:16.290
We're now in the
inject period.

00:34:16.290 --> 00:34:18.139
We're going to get better,
faster, because it's built on

00:34:18.139 --> 00:34:21.390
the same technologies as
traditional printing.

00:34:21.390 --> 00:34:24.199
You know how Apple's slogan,
when it released

00:34:24.199 --> 00:34:25.290
the iPod, was "Rip.

00:34:25.290 --> 00:34:25.889
Mix.

00:34:25.889 --> 00:34:28.370
Burn." And that changed
the music industry.

00:34:28.370 --> 00:34:31.250
The idea that you could take
music, professional music, and

00:34:31.250 --> 00:34:33.909
you could rip it, bring
it into your computer.

00:34:33.909 --> 00:34:35.550
Then you could change
it, mix it.

00:34:35.550 --> 00:34:38.080
Then you could produce it.

00:34:38.080 --> 00:34:39.510
Then you could make your
own CDs and distribute

00:34:39.510 --> 00:34:41.790
them and burn them.

00:34:41.790 --> 00:34:45.340
That idea, that sense of
control, that sense that the

00:34:45.340 --> 00:34:48.190
tools of production now were
within your reach, that was

00:34:48.190 --> 00:34:49.650
incredibly powerful.

00:34:49.650 --> 00:34:51.699
And it was scary for
the music industry.

00:34:51.699 --> 00:34:55.489
But it also unleashed this
explosion of creativity and

00:34:55.489 --> 00:34:57.460
changed the music industry,
I think, for the better.

00:34:57.460 --> 00:34:59.150
Adobe's slogan is "Rip.

00:34:59.150 --> 00:34:59.510
Mod.

00:34:59.510 --> 00:35:02.380
Make." And what does
that mean?

00:35:02.380 --> 00:35:04.760
How do you rip physical stuff?

00:35:04.760 --> 00:35:08.750
And the answer is called
reality capture.

00:35:08.750 --> 00:35:11.670
Right now, what you're seeing
right there is an app which is

00:35:11.670 --> 00:35:15.430
free on iPhone or IOS,
iPhone and iPad,

00:35:15.430 --> 00:35:17.480
which uses the camera.

00:35:17.480 --> 00:35:18.320
You just take pictures.

00:35:18.320 --> 00:35:19.520
You move around an object
and go click, click,

00:35:19.520 --> 00:35:20.600
click, click, click.

00:35:20.600 --> 00:35:22.400
It sends the pictures
up into the cloud.

00:35:22.400 --> 00:35:23.630
It stitches them together.

00:35:23.630 --> 00:35:27.810
And then it generates
a polygon mesh.

00:35:27.810 --> 00:35:30.020
It's scans reality.

00:35:30.020 --> 00:35:33.200
We can now capture reality, at
relatively low resolution, but

00:35:33.200 --> 00:35:33.770
they get better.

00:35:33.770 --> 00:35:36.580
So 3D scanning, which used to be
really hard, is now a free

00:35:36.580 --> 00:35:38.500
app in your phone.

00:35:38.500 --> 00:35:41.260
And what you do with it is
you then output the mesh.

00:35:41.260 --> 00:35:41.830
You then clean the mesh up.

00:35:41.830 --> 00:35:43.390
And then you, of course, print
your head as a Pez dispenser,

00:35:43.390 --> 00:35:44.370
as one does.

00:35:44.370 --> 00:35:46.120
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:46.120 --> 00:35:46.740
CHRIS ANDERSON: That's "Rip.

00:35:46.740 --> 00:35:47.140
Mod.

00:35:47.140 --> 00:35:48.010
Make," right?

00:35:48.010 --> 00:35:49.760
OK, it's a trivial example,
but think how

00:35:49.760 --> 00:35:51.930
powerful that is.

00:35:51.930 --> 00:35:54.600
We don't have to learn CAD
tools, we can just capture

00:35:54.600 --> 00:35:58.300
reality and fix it, make it our
own, adapt it, and then

00:35:58.300 --> 00:36:01.010
print it in whatever
material we want.

00:36:01.010 --> 00:36:02.920
We saw what it did to
the music industry.

00:36:02.920 --> 00:36:05.255
Just imagine what this might
do to everything else.

00:36:08.280 --> 00:36:09.630
Let's pull back.

00:36:09.630 --> 00:36:11.530
What does this mean
for the world?

00:36:11.530 --> 00:36:12.930
Was does this mean
for industry?

00:36:12.930 --> 00:36:15.450
What does this mean
for the economy?

00:36:15.450 --> 00:36:19.480
I started by saying that the
real revolution of the web was

00:36:19.480 --> 00:36:21.810
the innovation model, the fact
that we were able to bring

00:36:21.810 --> 00:36:24.420
everybody in and get them
to work together.

00:36:24.420 --> 00:36:28.050
And we now have an opportunity
do this with physical goods.

00:36:28.050 --> 00:36:30.720
I think what this creates is a
different kind of company.

00:36:30.720 --> 00:36:33.380
The guy on the left here
is Ronald Coase.

00:36:33.380 --> 00:36:36.860
He was the University of Chicago
economist who came up

00:36:36.860 --> 00:36:38.683
with the, so-called,
Theory of the Firm.

00:36:38.683 --> 00:36:42.770
In the 1930s, he was puzzling
over the question, why do

00:36:42.770 --> 00:36:44.160
companies exist.

00:36:44.160 --> 00:36:48.830
Why do we go to work under one
roof and for one company and

00:36:48.830 --> 00:36:52.140
with one job description and
with an aligned mission?

00:36:52.140 --> 00:36:53.180
Why do we do that?

00:36:53.180 --> 00:36:56.000
Why have we created
the corporation?

00:36:56.000 --> 00:37:00.190
And he came up with the theory
of transaction costs.

00:37:00.190 --> 00:37:01.160
We work for a company.

00:37:01.160 --> 00:37:04.140
You guys sit here and work for
Google, because it's the

00:37:04.140 --> 00:37:05.600
fastest way to get
things done.

00:37:05.600 --> 00:37:07.730
Transaction costs are the costs
of communicating with

00:37:07.730 --> 00:37:08.420
each other.

00:37:08.420 --> 00:37:10.317
And because each of you has a
role and responsibility, you

00:37:10.317 --> 00:37:11.970
know who does what.

00:37:11.970 --> 00:37:14.490
So Accounts Receivable is here
and Accounts Payable is there.

00:37:14.490 --> 00:37:17.910
And you know how to find the
person to get stuff done.

00:37:17.910 --> 00:37:19.400
That's great.

00:37:19.400 --> 00:37:22.370
20th century thanks
you for that.

00:37:22.370 --> 00:37:23.380
And it worked fine.

00:37:23.380 --> 00:37:25.360
However, the guy on the right,
Bill Joy, one of the

00:37:25.360 --> 00:37:28.950
co-founders of Sun Microsystems,
accepted that.

00:37:28.950 --> 00:37:30.270
And he worked for a company.

00:37:30.270 --> 00:37:33.250
But he did reflect on one of
the truisms, which is, he

00:37:33.250 --> 00:37:35.800
said, "Whoever you are, the
smartest people in the world

00:37:35.800 --> 00:37:38.030
don't work for you." This is
probably the one place in the

00:37:38.030 --> 00:37:38.680
world where that's not true.

00:37:38.680 --> 00:37:39.626
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:39.626 --> 00:37:42.250
CHRIS ANDERSON: But it was
generally a truism, which is

00:37:42.250 --> 00:37:45.690
to say, statistically speaking,
for any given job,

00:37:45.690 --> 00:37:48.495
the smartest person in the world
is not the person who

00:37:48.495 --> 00:37:50.460
has that defined role and
responsibility and is in the

00:37:50.460 --> 00:37:51.650
cubicle next to you.

00:37:51.650 --> 00:37:53.270
They're probably out
there somewhere.

00:37:53.270 --> 00:37:56.365
They're probably in China or
India or whatever, but how are

00:37:56.365 --> 00:37:57.060
you going to find them?

00:37:57.060 --> 00:37:58.070
Right?

00:37:58.070 --> 00:38:01.480
The transaction costs of finding
the statistically

00:38:01.480 --> 00:38:05.530
smartest person in the world for
that job are too high, so

00:38:05.530 --> 00:38:07.840
you settle for the
one you're with.

00:38:07.840 --> 00:38:09.420
By the way, if you think about
it, this is probably true for

00:38:09.420 --> 00:38:10.850
your spouse as well.

00:38:10.850 --> 00:38:11.740
And we just--

00:38:11.740 --> 00:38:12.250
don't go there.

00:38:12.250 --> 00:38:12.713
You go absolutely crazy.

00:38:12.713 --> 00:38:13.176
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:13.176 --> 00:38:15.700
CHRIS ANDERSON: You know, the
odds of the perfect person for

00:38:15.700 --> 00:38:19.000
you happened to grow up in your
town, so we love the one

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:20.800
we're with.

00:38:20.800 --> 00:38:25.400
However, that's sub-optimal.

00:38:25.400 --> 00:38:30.420
It's like what we do with things
like what school did

00:38:30.420 --> 00:38:33.690
you go to, what grades did you
get, let me see your CV, your

00:38:33.690 --> 00:38:36.930
track record, let's get the
references, are you available,

00:38:36.930 --> 00:38:38.440
do you speak the right language,
do you have the

00:38:38.440 --> 00:38:42.430
right visa, those are not
talent-optimizing.

00:38:42.430 --> 00:38:43.980
They are basically
access-optimizing.

00:38:43.980 --> 00:38:46.040
What we do is we're settling
for the safest

00:38:46.040 --> 00:38:47.170
person in the world.

00:38:47.170 --> 00:38:49.740
We know this person
can do the job.

00:38:49.740 --> 00:38:53.550
And the 20th century talent
filters were largely oriented

00:38:53.550 --> 00:38:57.180
around minimizing the difficulty
in finding someone

00:38:57.180 --> 00:38:58.250
who could do the job.

00:38:58.250 --> 00:38:59.930
But we didn't end up with
the right person.

00:38:59.930 --> 00:39:02.480
We didn't end up with the
best person for the job.

00:39:02.480 --> 00:39:05.820
So I wanted to end with a story
about my own little

00:39:05.820 --> 00:39:08.740
adventure in this and how we may
have solved Joy's paradox.

00:39:08.740 --> 00:39:11.970
This is the cover of "Make
Magazine," which is the Bible

00:39:11.970 --> 00:39:15.780
of the movement, the
Maker Movement.

00:39:15.780 --> 00:39:19.630
And my little adventure with
my children, starting with

00:39:19.630 --> 00:39:21.540
blimps, went down
the rabbit hole.

00:39:21.540 --> 00:39:23.150
I'll show you in
a few minutes.

00:39:23.150 --> 00:39:24.780
But I ended up getting
into drums.

00:39:24.780 --> 00:39:26.590
And I built a community.

00:39:26.590 --> 00:39:29.000
And I met that guy there,
Jordi Munoz.

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:31.880
And I just want to tell a little
story about Jordi And

00:39:31.880 --> 00:39:32.480
then we'll end.

00:39:32.480 --> 00:39:35.660
And we'll take questions.

00:39:35.660 --> 00:39:38.240
So my own adventure with this
started with trying to get my

00:39:38.240 --> 00:39:39.900
kids interested in science
and technology.

00:39:39.900 --> 00:39:42.460
I started a site called GeekDad,
which is now run by

00:39:42.460 --> 00:39:42.920
other people.

00:39:42.920 --> 00:39:47.170
But this is my eternal and
eternally unsuccessful quest,

00:39:47.170 --> 00:39:49.560
to get my kids more geeky.

00:39:49.560 --> 00:39:52.740
I've got five kids.

00:39:52.740 --> 00:39:57.580
And every weekend I'd try to
find science and technology

00:39:57.580 --> 00:40:00.980
projects that were fun for
them and fun for me.

00:40:00.980 --> 00:40:04.180
So one Friday at the office at
"Wired," we got in a LEGO

00:40:04.180 --> 00:40:04.810
Mindstorms kit.

00:40:04.810 --> 00:40:06.620
And this was right before
they came out.

00:40:06.620 --> 00:40:07.710
So we got one of
the first ones.

00:40:07.710 --> 00:40:09.220
And we got a radio controlled
airplane.

00:40:09.220 --> 00:40:11.570
I thought, best weekend
ever, right?

00:40:11.570 --> 00:40:15.660
So on Saturday, we're going to
make a robot out of LEGO.

00:40:15.660 --> 00:40:17.250
And on Sunday, we're going to
fly a plane in the park.

00:40:17.250 --> 00:40:18.980
How could this go wrong?

00:40:18.980 --> 00:40:19.880
This is Erin.

00:40:19.880 --> 00:40:21.410
She was nine.

00:40:21.410 --> 00:40:23.070
She's building the first
project of the LEGO

00:40:23.070 --> 00:40:23.530
Mindstorms.

00:40:23.530 --> 00:40:24.065
It's a tripod.

00:40:24.065 --> 00:40:26.090
It's a three-wheeled robot.

00:40:26.090 --> 00:40:28.690
And what you do is you put
together the robot.

00:40:28.690 --> 00:40:32.660
And then you use this visual
programming language built on

00:40:32.660 --> 00:40:33.330
[? LabVIEW ?]

00:40:33.330 --> 00:40:34.820
to program it.

00:40:34.820 --> 00:40:38.440
And there's Daniel, 11.

00:40:38.440 --> 00:40:41.630
And he's getting ready to
push the button and see

00:40:41.630 --> 00:40:42.950
whether it will work.

00:40:42.950 --> 00:40:48.125
So what it does is it goes
forward until it sees a wall.

00:40:48.125 --> 00:40:50.590
And then it backs up.

00:40:50.590 --> 00:40:53.410
And my kids are like, you've
got to be kidding.

00:40:53.410 --> 00:40:56.380
We've seen "Transformers."
We know what robots

00:40:56.380 --> 00:40:57.030
are supposed to do.

00:40:57.030 --> 00:40:58.570
Where are the lasers?

00:40:58.570 --> 00:41:00.560
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:00.560 --> 00:41:03.580
CHRIS ANDERSON: This is not a
death-dealing, three-story

00:41:03.580 --> 00:41:06.170
killing machine.

00:41:06.170 --> 00:41:08.570
Hollywood has ruined robotics
for children.

00:41:08.570 --> 00:41:11.440
You cannot compete with CG.

00:41:11.440 --> 00:41:13.590
So they were really
disappointed and

00:41:13.590 --> 00:41:14.520
lost interest entirely.

00:41:14.520 --> 00:41:16.820
And so I was a little
upset about that.

00:41:16.820 --> 00:41:17.870
So I said OK--

00:41:17.870 --> 00:41:20.850
that was Saturday-- on Sunday,
we're going to fly a plane.

00:41:20.850 --> 00:41:21.970
This is the plane we got.

00:41:21.970 --> 00:41:22.950
And so we went to the park.

00:41:22.950 --> 00:41:24.170
And we'd seen YouTube videos.

00:41:24.170 --> 00:41:25.700
And it looked awfully cool.

00:41:25.700 --> 00:41:28.430
And this is what happened.

00:41:28.430 --> 00:41:29.350
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:29.350 --> 00:41:31.710
CHRIS ANDERSON: So I flew
it into a tree.

00:41:31.710 --> 00:41:34.160
And if that weren't humiliating
enough, it was dad

00:41:34.160 --> 00:41:36.260
climbing into the tree to get
it back, which is completely

00:41:36.260 --> 00:41:37.000
mortifying.

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:37.730
And.

00:41:37.730 --> 00:41:39.560
I had to bribe them
with ice cream.

00:41:39.560 --> 00:41:41.800
And it was a bad scene.

00:41:41.800 --> 00:41:43.700
And once again, they were
reminded that any time Dad

00:41:43.700 --> 00:41:45.590
wants to do science and
technology projects, it ends

00:41:45.590 --> 00:41:47.790
up as a disaster.

00:41:47.790 --> 00:41:49.760
So I was kind of annoyed
about the whole thing.

00:41:49.760 --> 00:41:51.840
And went for a run
to clear my head.

00:41:51.840 --> 00:41:52.830
And I was out there thinking.

00:41:52.830 --> 00:41:57.670
I was like, phew, that sucked.

00:41:57.670 --> 00:41:59.180
A, the robots weren't
very fun.

00:41:59.180 --> 00:42:01.010
They just ran into a wall.

00:42:01.010 --> 00:42:03.073
And B, I can't fly.

00:42:03.073 --> 00:42:05.620
I thought, god, I'll bet the
LEGO could have flown that

00:42:05.620 --> 00:42:07.870
plane better than me.

00:42:07.870 --> 00:42:10.410
And then I thought about the
sensors that came in the kit.

00:42:10.410 --> 00:42:14.310
And it came with a gyro sensor
and accelerometer, it's called

00:42:14.310 --> 00:42:17.515
tilt sensor, and a magnetometer,
which is called

00:42:17.515 --> 00:42:20.520
a compass sensor, and a
Bluetooth connection.

00:42:20.520 --> 00:42:22.650
And I was like, oh my god,
you could almost build an

00:42:22.650 --> 00:42:24.000
auto-pilot out of this.

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:24.600
So I came back.

00:42:24.600 --> 00:42:27.280
And I said, OK, kids,
one last thing.

00:42:27.280 --> 00:42:29.420
We're going to build
an auto-pilot.

00:42:29.420 --> 00:42:30.950
And this is what we
came up with.

00:42:30.950 --> 00:42:34.415
And this is a LEGO auto-pilot.

00:42:34.415 --> 00:42:37.190
It's got gyros, accelerometers,
magnetometers,

00:42:37.190 --> 00:42:38.400
a RC interface.

00:42:38.400 --> 00:42:40.210
It actually runs a
common filter.

00:42:40.210 --> 00:42:43.030
I actually had to Google
common filter.

00:42:43.030 --> 00:42:47.290
That was actually harder than
I expected to implement.

00:42:47.290 --> 00:42:50.660
I knew nothing about this, but
it kind of almost worked.

00:42:50.660 --> 00:42:52.500
We put it in a plane.

00:42:52.500 --> 00:42:55.080
It actually kind of
flew on its own.

00:42:55.080 --> 00:42:57.890
This we had posted on Slashdot
this is, I think, technically,

00:42:57.890 --> 00:43:01.670
the world's first LEGO unmanned
aerial vehicle, UAV.

00:43:01.670 --> 00:43:05.930
It's now in the LEGO museum
in Billund, which

00:43:05.930 --> 00:43:07.380
we're very proud of.

00:43:07.380 --> 00:43:13.010
The kids and I got to go to
LEGO, to Billund for that.

00:43:13.010 --> 00:43:14.720
And we learned a
lot about this.

00:43:14.720 --> 00:43:20.510
We learned A, that this stuff
is not that hard, B, that

00:43:20.510 --> 00:43:23.460
what's going on with the
smartphone revolution, what's

00:43:23.460 --> 00:43:27.020
going on in your pocket that the
revolution in MEM sensors

00:43:27.020 --> 00:43:30.690
and ARM processors and GPS and
wireless and cameras and

00:43:30.690 --> 00:43:35.990
memory and integration, all
this kind of stuff, this

00:43:35.990 --> 00:43:38.460
driving a technological wave
that we've only seen the

00:43:38.460 --> 00:43:39.730
beginnings of.

00:43:39.730 --> 00:43:42.810
I just realized, thanks to
Mindstorms, that you can fly a

00:43:42.810 --> 00:43:44.780
747 with this.

00:43:44.780 --> 00:43:47.270
With the right app and the right
cable, you've got a--

00:43:47.270 --> 00:43:49.440
not terribly well, I wouldn't
recommend it--

00:43:49.440 --> 00:43:50.860
but you've got all it takes.

00:43:50.860 --> 00:43:54.350
And that just as Jobs and
Wozniak realized that

00:43:54.350 --> 00:43:58.250
original, what was it, an 8088
processor, et cetera, was

00:43:58.250 --> 00:44:00.600
available, and relatively
cheap and easy to use.

00:44:00.600 --> 00:44:02.380
And then you could, maybe, build
a computer out of it.

00:44:02.380 --> 00:44:03.810
And that ended up with
the Apple II

00:44:03.810 --> 00:44:05.110
and changed the world.

00:44:05.110 --> 00:44:08.040
We're right there with
the guts of a

00:44:08.040 --> 00:44:08.660
smartphone right now.

00:44:08.660 --> 00:44:11.120
It has extraordinary
applications outside.

00:44:11.120 --> 00:44:13.960
And being able to fly a plane
is just one of them.

00:44:13.960 --> 00:44:15.890
Now, in the course of doing
this, we learned a lot.

00:44:15.890 --> 00:44:18.950
We learned that auto-pilots are
considered cruise missile

00:44:18.950 --> 00:44:22.240
controllers by the State
Department's International

00:44:22.240 --> 00:44:25.500
Trade in Arms Regulations,
ITAR.

00:44:25.500 --> 00:44:30.190
And that's by my nine-year-old
developing an auto-pilot and

00:44:30.190 --> 00:44:32.942
putting it online that we,
technically, weaponized LEGO.

00:44:32.942 --> 00:44:34.238
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:34.238 --> 00:44:37.890
CHRIS ANDERSON: So it was quite
a learning process.

00:44:37.890 --> 00:44:40.480
So what I did is I decided
to just learn in public.

00:44:40.480 --> 00:44:43.340
So I started a community called
DIY Drones and just

00:44:43.340 --> 00:44:44.470
basically shared my ignorance.

00:44:44.470 --> 00:44:45.450
I knew nothing.

00:44:45.450 --> 00:44:48.180
And I just kept asking dumb
questions like, what's a

00:44:48.180 --> 00:44:49.970
common filter?

00:44:49.970 --> 00:44:52.650
And digital electronics, and
analog electronics, and

00:44:52.650 --> 00:44:56.720
aerodynamics, and dynamic
systems, and control theory,

00:44:56.720 --> 00:45:00.420
and I knew nothing about this.

00:45:00.420 --> 00:45:01.500
Everything I found, I shared.

00:45:01.500 --> 00:45:03.040
And people kept answering
my questions.

00:45:03.040 --> 00:45:05.030
And today, we're one of the
biggest robotics communities

00:45:05.030 --> 00:45:06.280
in the world.

00:45:08.720 --> 00:45:12.040
And people here at Google who
are probably members, and

00:45:12.040 --> 00:45:13.890
Apple, and Microsoft,
and IBM, et cetera.

00:45:13.890 --> 00:45:16.420
And by day, they do
awesome work here.

00:45:16.420 --> 00:45:19.060
And by night, they do awesome
work in auto-pilots and

00:45:19.060 --> 00:45:21.250
drones, et cetera, because
they're really into it.

00:45:21.250 --> 00:45:26.500
And we ended up, by accident,
competing with

00:45:26.500 --> 00:45:28.560
the aerospace industry.

00:45:28.560 --> 00:45:29.460
This is what we do.

00:45:29.460 --> 00:45:31.660
We make these auto-pilots
right now.

00:45:31.660 --> 00:45:34.120
We work with ETH in Zurich.

00:45:34.120 --> 00:45:36.390
The Swiss, by the way, turned
out-- thank you, grandpa--

00:45:36.390 --> 00:45:39.570
turned out to be the leaders in
robotics, because all those

00:45:39.570 --> 00:45:41.770
watch makers had extraordinary
mechanical skills.

00:45:41.770 --> 00:45:43.350
And robots used to
be mechanical.

00:45:43.350 --> 00:45:45.830
And now ETH and EPFL, which
are the two leading

00:45:45.830 --> 00:45:48.570
universities-- it's like
the MIT and Stanford--

00:45:48.570 --> 00:45:50.770
when I asked them to make that
connection, they say, well no,

00:45:50.770 --> 00:45:52.233
the most important thing is one
is German-speaking and one

00:45:52.233 --> 00:45:54.080
is French-speaking, so you can't
really make the MIT,

00:45:54.080 --> 00:45:55.140
Stanford connection.

00:45:55.140 --> 00:45:56.520
But anyway, they're
really good.

00:45:56.520 --> 00:45:57.760
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:57.760 --> 00:46:00.880
CHRIS ANDERSON: And so anyway,
we work with them.

00:46:00.880 --> 00:46:04.820
And this is the stuff
we make now.

00:46:04.820 --> 00:46:08.850
This is like military grade
auto-pilots which are built on

00:46:08.850 --> 00:46:14.010
smartphone chips and
sell for $140.

00:46:14.010 --> 00:46:17.180
The Parrott AR.Drone, which some
of you may have and is a

00:46:17.180 --> 00:46:20.210
lovely piece of gear, it's a
quadricopter that you can

00:46:20.210 --> 00:46:22.990
control with an iPhone
or an Android.

00:46:22.990 --> 00:46:24.940
It's not really a drone,
I hate to tell you.

00:46:24.940 --> 00:46:28.200
Drones are autonomous, fully
autonomous, automatic takeoff,

00:46:28.200 --> 00:46:30.710
landing, missions, GPS
coordinates, et cetera.

00:46:30.710 --> 00:46:31.590
Our drone is teleoperated.

00:46:31.590 --> 00:46:33.210
It's remote control.

00:46:33.210 --> 00:46:36.810
Unless you rip out the guts and
put in our stuff, and then

00:46:36.810 --> 00:46:38.290
it's a real drone.

00:46:38.290 --> 00:46:41.450
So that's where we're
going on this.

00:46:41.450 --> 00:46:46.180
Just a little segue into why
this is happening now.

00:46:46.180 --> 00:46:48.290
It turns out that these
multi-copters, these

00:46:48.290 --> 00:46:51.080
quadricopters, are basically
solid state devices.

00:46:51.080 --> 00:46:53.370
But they don't have any moving
parts, except for the motors

00:46:53.370 --> 00:46:53.850
themselves.

00:46:53.850 --> 00:46:57.260
But they were not possible
until about a decade ago,

00:46:57.260 --> 00:46:59.190
because they're essentially
unstable.

00:46:59.190 --> 00:47:01.190
You can't fly them manually.

00:47:01.190 --> 00:47:05.130
You need a basic computer on
board to spin the props to go

00:47:05.130 --> 00:47:07.030
clockwise, to go
counter-clockwise, and just

00:47:07.030 --> 00:47:08.720
getting the math right.

00:47:08.720 --> 00:47:12.180
It needs to happen at 400 times
a second, 400 Hertz.

00:47:12.180 --> 00:47:14.640
But once you get it right, you
can do all sorts of amazing

00:47:14.640 --> 00:47:16.160
configurations.

00:47:16.160 --> 00:47:17.410
It's just math, right?

00:47:17.410 --> 00:47:23.240
It's just these look-up tables
that can control any shape,

00:47:23.240 --> 00:47:25.880
and how big a camera you want
to lift, whether you want to

00:47:25.880 --> 00:47:32.020
have an open field of view for
a camera, whether you want

00:47:32.020 --> 00:47:33.700
redundancy of motors,
et cetera.

00:47:33.700 --> 00:47:35.230
This is just math.

00:47:35.230 --> 00:47:39.150
And it's really kind of exciting
that you can now come

00:47:39.150 --> 00:47:42.500
up with these extraordinary
and before impossible

00:47:42.500 --> 00:47:45.980
configurations of aircraft and
fly them with an auto-pilot

00:47:45.980 --> 00:47:49.630
that costs just over $100.

00:47:49.630 --> 00:47:50.720
So we ended up with this.

00:47:50.720 --> 00:47:52.980
We started with the
Arduino platform.

00:47:52.980 --> 00:47:56.000
And actually, I have one of
the auto-pilots here.

00:47:56.000 --> 00:47:57.250
Here, I'll just grab it here.

00:48:01.440 --> 00:48:02.770
This is an auto-pilot
right here.

00:48:02.770 --> 00:48:04.940
It's just a little box.

00:48:04.940 --> 00:48:07.600
And you put this little
box in any vehicle.

00:48:07.600 --> 00:48:10.540
And it suddenly becomes a fully
autonomous drone, and

00:48:10.540 --> 00:48:12.080
including a car.

00:48:12.080 --> 00:48:15.390
Not quite as good as your
autonomous car, but this one's

00:48:15.390 --> 00:48:17.010
a lot cheaper.

00:48:17.010 --> 00:48:17.950
[LAUGHTER]

00:48:17.950 --> 00:48:19.880
CHRIS ANDERSON: You know, you
could put it in anything.

00:48:19.880 --> 00:48:21.250
I don't have a boat up
there, but you can

00:48:21.250 --> 00:48:22.040
do boats, et cetera.

00:48:22.040 --> 00:48:23.270
But this is kind of magical.

00:48:23.270 --> 00:48:26.380
This is basically a triple-core,
Arduino board,

00:48:26.380 --> 00:48:28.450
GPS, lots of sensors,
et cetera.

00:48:28.450 --> 00:48:31.830
You just stick this in any
vehicle, and suddenly it's

00:48:31.830 --> 00:48:35.860
like a military grade UAV, minus
the weapons, of course.

00:48:35.860 --> 00:48:38.210
And then you've got these
ground stations.

00:48:38.210 --> 00:48:39.820
And you just point and
click waypoints.

00:48:39.820 --> 00:48:40.850
And you give mission commands.

00:48:40.850 --> 00:48:41.710
And it's scriptable.

00:48:41.710 --> 00:48:43.560
And you can script it
in Python or just

00:48:43.560 --> 00:48:44.520
manually like this.

00:48:44.520 --> 00:48:46.990
And automatic takeoff, and
landing, and loiter, and

00:48:46.990 --> 00:48:48.000
camera control.

00:48:48.000 --> 00:48:50.860
And we have this cool Follow-me
function where you

00:48:50.860 --> 00:48:52.290
have it in a box that looks
a little like this.

00:48:52.290 --> 00:48:53.850
And let's say you're windsurfing
out there on the

00:48:53.850 --> 00:48:57.100
bay and you're really
doing well.

00:48:57.100 --> 00:48:58.250
And this is the GoPro
era, right?

00:48:58.250 --> 00:49:00.990
You totally need this
on YouTube.

00:49:00.990 --> 00:49:02.170
So what you just do is
you just push the

00:49:02.170 --> 00:49:04.640
button in the box.

00:49:04.640 --> 00:49:07.880
And your quadricopter with the
GoPro takes off from the

00:49:07.880 --> 00:49:11.140
beach, comes out to you,
positions itself 30 feet

00:49:11.140 --> 00:49:13.660
behind and 30 feet above you,
and then just follows you

00:49:13.660 --> 00:49:16.960
around as you do your thing with
the camera focused on you

00:49:16.960 --> 00:49:18.040
the whole time.

00:49:18.040 --> 00:49:19.150
And when the battery
gets low, it flies

00:49:19.150 --> 00:49:21.510
itself back to the beach.

00:49:21.510 --> 00:49:22.690
That's the Follow-me function.

00:49:22.690 --> 00:49:26.990
That's like the droids, you know
the personal droids in

00:49:26.990 --> 00:49:28.240
Star Wars, right?

00:49:28.240 --> 00:49:29.470
This is now possible.

00:49:29.470 --> 00:49:31.660
There are people doing
it right now.

00:49:31.660 --> 00:49:34.690
And this didn't come to
you from Boeing or

00:49:34.690 --> 00:49:35.590
from Lockheed Martin.

00:49:35.590 --> 00:49:38.320
It came to you from a community
of amateurs--

00:49:38.320 --> 00:49:40.440
we all have day jobs but, by
this, we're amateurs--

00:49:40.440 --> 00:49:42.540
working together using the web's
innovation model and

00:49:42.540 --> 00:49:46.050
open platforms like Arduino.

00:49:46.050 --> 00:49:47.940
So what we ended up
doing was being--

00:49:47.940 --> 00:49:49.740
and we ended up part of the
Open Hardware Movement.

00:49:49.740 --> 00:49:51.180
So MakerBot's open hardware.

00:49:51.180 --> 00:49:52.020
And there's a number
of others.

00:49:52.020 --> 00:49:57.590
But we realized that, by
accident, we'd figured out a

00:49:57.590 --> 00:49:59.520
way, along with many others, to

00:49:59.520 --> 00:50:00.940
industrialize the Maker Movement.

00:50:00.940 --> 00:50:03.270
We give away the bits
in the community.

00:50:03.270 --> 00:50:04.730
That software is all open.

00:50:04.730 --> 00:50:08.720
And then we sell the atoms in
the form of hardware with a

00:50:08.720 --> 00:50:10.650
robotic company.

00:50:10.650 --> 00:50:13.490
We don't have the best
technology in the world, but

00:50:13.490 --> 00:50:14.900
we have the cheapest technology
in the world.

00:50:14.900 --> 00:50:16.380
And we have the best innovation

00:50:16.380 --> 00:50:17.740
model, which is open.

00:50:17.740 --> 00:50:21.900
And the ability to apply the
web's innovation model to

00:50:21.900 --> 00:50:25.850
physical goods is the real tool
here, just in the same

00:50:25.850 --> 00:50:29.910
way the technologists created
TCP/IP and HTML, et cetera.

00:50:29.910 --> 00:50:32.570
But we, the regular people,
filled it with our ideas.

00:50:32.570 --> 00:50:34.490
And that's right where
we are with hardware.

00:50:34.490 --> 00:50:37.950
The technology is there
and easy and in place.

00:50:37.950 --> 00:50:40.410
And now we can just fill
it with our ideas.

00:50:40.410 --> 00:50:43.170
And the nice thing about
hardware is that there's no

00:50:43.170 --> 00:50:45.030
crazy debate over the
business model.

00:50:45.030 --> 00:50:46.980
The business model is you
sell products for

00:50:46.980 --> 00:50:48.206
more than they cost.

00:50:48.206 --> 00:50:49.200
Period.

00:50:49.200 --> 00:50:51.710
That's it.

00:50:51.710 --> 00:50:54.040
Business schools professors
keep saying, explain your

00:50:54.040 --> 00:50:54.220
business model.

00:50:54.220 --> 00:50:57.272
It's like, we sell products
for more than they cost.

00:50:57.272 --> 00:50:59.120
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:59.120 --> 00:51:00.800
CHRIS ANDERSON: We made
money on Day 1.

00:51:00.800 --> 00:51:04.330
We actually sell it at 2.6
times the actual cost.

00:51:04.330 --> 00:51:07.760
2.6, that cost is the Bill
of Materials plus labor.

00:51:07.760 --> 00:51:09.440
And 2.6 is like this
magic number.

00:51:09.440 --> 00:51:12.130
It's basically two 40% margins,
one for us, and one

00:51:12.130 --> 00:51:15.070
for our distribution partners,
a wholesale and a retail

00:51:15.070 --> 00:51:16.970
margin, if you will, 2.6.

00:51:16.970 --> 00:51:19.310
2.6 times the Bill of Materials
is like an order of

00:51:19.310 --> 00:51:21.480
magnitude cheaper than
closed-source, sometimes two

00:51:21.480 --> 00:51:23.460
orders of magnitude cheaper.

00:51:23.460 --> 00:51:25.070
It's not rocket science.

00:51:25.070 --> 00:51:26.170
We learned it from other
people in the

00:51:26.170 --> 00:51:28.340
Open Hardware Movement.

00:51:28.340 --> 00:51:30.590
But it works great.

00:51:30.590 --> 00:51:32.590
And the customers do the product
development for us.

00:51:32.590 --> 00:51:33.810
They design the products
for us.

00:51:33.810 --> 00:51:34.600
They then give it to us.

00:51:34.600 --> 00:51:36.150
We then sell it back to them.

00:51:36.150 --> 00:51:39.980
If it's not right, they
fix it for us.

00:51:39.980 --> 00:51:41.370
If it needs customer support,
they do the

00:51:41.370 --> 00:51:42.290
customer support for us.

00:51:42.290 --> 00:51:43.540
They write the documentation.

00:51:46.150 --> 00:51:47.230
They catch our bugs.

00:51:47.230 --> 00:51:48.650
They do our regression
testing.

00:51:48.650 --> 00:51:49.936
It's just wonderful.

00:51:49.936 --> 00:51:50.280
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:50.280 --> 00:51:52.660
CHRIS ANDERSON: Now, it's also
an incredible obligation and

00:51:52.660 --> 00:51:53.970
responsibility.

00:51:53.970 --> 00:51:56.280
Every morning, I wake up
to lots of customers

00:51:56.280 --> 00:51:57.140
with lots of demands.

00:51:57.140 --> 00:52:00.520
But the point is is that the
web's innovation model works

00:52:00.520 --> 00:52:01.340
in the real world.

00:52:01.340 --> 00:52:04.600
And we've seen what it does in
electronics, but just imagine

00:52:04.600 --> 00:52:07.410
what it can do in
everything else.

00:52:07.410 --> 00:52:08.640
So I just wanted to end
with that story.

00:52:08.640 --> 00:52:10.360
Jordi, I told you about Jordi.

00:52:10.360 --> 00:52:11.990
I showed you a picture
of Jordi Munoz.

00:52:11.990 --> 00:52:14.430
And I just wanted to tell
you what happened.

00:52:14.430 --> 00:52:17.490
So when we started DIY Drones,
it became clear that we needed

00:52:17.490 --> 00:52:20.090
to make a company.

00:52:20.090 --> 00:52:22.650
We put the files out there,
and we said, here.

00:52:22.650 --> 00:52:24.020
Here's the PCB file.

00:52:24.020 --> 00:52:25.160
Just have it batched.

00:52:25.160 --> 00:52:27.400
And then order the components
from DigiKey

00:52:27.400 --> 00:52:28.490
and then solder it.

00:52:28.490 --> 00:52:29.750
Come on.

00:52:29.750 --> 00:52:31.540
And people were like, could you
do that for us, because

00:52:31.540 --> 00:52:33.040
that's actually kind of hard.

00:52:33.040 --> 00:52:34.900
And we said, OK.

00:52:34.900 --> 00:52:36.940
And so we started on the kitchen
table hand soldering.

00:52:36.940 --> 00:52:37.560
And that was no fun.

00:52:37.560 --> 00:52:40.330
And then we sent it to China
and realized that, when you

00:52:40.330 --> 00:52:41.770
have to get economies of scale,
you have to order

00:52:41.770 --> 00:52:44.225
1,000, which means that, if
it's wrong, you just have

00:52:44.225 --> 00:52:45.230
1,000 dead boards.

00:52:45.230 --> 00:52:47.885
And also, if you order 1,000
boards or 10,000 boards, you

00:52:47.885 --> 00:52:50.180
actually have to sell them
before you change the design,

00:52:50.180 --> 00:52:53.040
or else all your money is
sunk in dead boards.

00:52:53.040 --> 00:52:54.760
And so we then brought
it back.

00:52:54.760 --> 00:52:56.120
And we said, well, we'll do
our own manufacturing.

00:52:56.120 --> 00:52:56.990
We'll start a factory.

00:52:56.990 --> 00:52:59.360
And so we started it in
a garage, as one does.

00:52:59.360 --> 00:53:02.150
There's Jordi on the right.

00:53:02.150 --> 00:53:06.240
Oh, by the way, Jordi was the
guy who just was doing the

00:53:06.240 --> 00:53:07.180
cool stuff in the forum.

00:53:07.180 --> 00:53:10.660
He was flying a helicopter
with a Wii controller.

00:53:10.660 --> 00:53:11.900
And he posted YouTube videos.

00:53:11.900 --> 00:53:13.090
And he showed he could do it.

00:53:13.090 --> 00:53:15.750
And so I'm like, that
guy is awesome.

00:53:15.750 --> 00:53:16.750
He knows all the cool stuff.

00:53:16.750 --> 00:53:18.290
He turned me on to Arduino.

00:53:18.290 --> 00:53:20.950
And I said, Jordi, do you want
to start a company together?

00:53:20.950 --> 00:53:21.780
And he said, sure.

00:53:21.780 --> 00:53:23.500
I said, tell me a little
something about yourself.

00:53:23.500 --> 00:53:26.430
And he turned out to be a
19-year-old from Tijuana.

00:53:26.430 --> 00:53:28.530
He just graduated from
high school.

00:53:28.530 --> 00:53:32.630
And today, he's the CEO
of 3D Robotics.

00:53:32.630 --> 00:53:35.270
This is like a tiny corner of
one of our two factories.

00:53:35.270 --> 00:53:39.630
We have one in San Diego
and one in Tijuana.

00:53:39.630 --> 00:53:42.100
We've got something like
24,000 square foot of

00:53:42.100 --> 00:53:42.700
[? pick-and-place ?]

00:53:42.700 --> 00:53:47.810
lines and CNC machines
and 50 workers

00:53:47.810 --> 00:53:48.950
right now and engineers.

00:53:48.950 --> 00:53:52.190
And we put twice as
many drones in the

00:53:52.190 --> 00:53:54.630
air as the US military.

00:53:54.630 --> 00:53:56.890
Our drones cost $600 and are
made out of plastic.

00:53:56.890 --> 00:53:59.410
And theirs cost $6 million and
are not made out of plastic.

00:53:59.410 --> 00:53:59.740
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:59.740 --> 00:54:00.930
CHRIS ANDERSON: But
still, we've got

00:54:00.930 --> 00:54:02.170
15,000 of them out there.

00:54:02.170 --> 00:54:03.930
And the military has 7,000.

00:54:03.930 --> 00:54:08.130
And Jordi has built this
by basically buying--

00:54:08.130 --> 00:54:09.760
the first [? pick-and-place ?]
we got on eBay.

00:54:09.760 --> 00:54:12.220
And he looked up the
manual on Google.

00:54:12.220 --> 00:54:16.260
And today, we're going for
ISO 9000 compliance.

00:54:16.260 --> 00:54:19.080
And that was three years.

00:54:19.080 --> 00:54:23.170
So that's the answer
to Joy's paradox.

00:54:23.170 --> 00:54:26.220
10 years ago, when the editor of
"Wired" was going to start

00:54:26.220 --> 00:54:29.110
a drone company, what are the
odds that he would end up with

00:54:29.110 --> 00:54:31.180
a Mexican teenager
from Tijuana?

00:54:31.180 --> 00:54:34.950
And yet, that was the best
person in the world for this

00:54:34.950 --> 00:54:36.810
job, that he was the smartest
person in the world.

00:54:36.810 --> 00:54:39.930
He failed all the 20th century
tests of talent acquisition.

00:54:39.930 --> 00:54:42.190
He did not speak the right
language, come from the right

00:54:42.190 --> 00:54:45.660
country, have the right degree
or any degree, have any

00:54:45.660 --> 00:54:47.310
professional experience.

00:54:47.310 --> 00:54:47.900
He would have failed.

00:54:47.900 --> 00:54:50.040
He would not have worked.

00:54:50.040 --> 00:54:54.950
Maybe your admission standards
have changed at Google, but by

00:54:54.950 --> 00:54:57.830
and large, I suspect he would
have failed your tests.

00:54:57.830 --> 00:55:01.610
And yet, he passed the test of
the web's talent discovery

00:55:01.610 --> 00:55:02.990
model, which is that
he could do it.

00:55:02.990 --> 00:55:04.540
And he showed what
he could do.

00:55:07.420 --> 00:55:09.625
Actually, I asked him questions
like, tell me a

00:55:09.625 --> 00:55:10.050
little something
about yourself.

00:55:10.050 --> 00:55:11.680
But it didn't matter any more.

00:55:11.680 --> 00:55:14.110
He'd already proven his
ability to do it.

00:55:14.110 --> 00:55:19.120
And today, it turns out it's
the best in the world.

00:55:19.120 --> 00:55:21.650
I thought I was picking him
because he knew a lot about

00:55:21.650 --> 00:55:23.790
technology, and he was really
innovative, and he turned me

00:55:23.790 --> 00:55:24.550
on to Arduino.

00:55:24.550 --> 00:55:26.310
But in fact, his real
asset was that he

00:55:26.310 --> 00:55:29.090
turned me on to Mexico.

00:55:29.090 --> 00:55:32.690
We have a second plant
in Tijuana.

00:55:32.690 --> 00:55:35.050
You may think of Tijuana as
being cheap tequila and drug

00:55:35.050 --> 00:55:39.270
cartels, but it's the Shenzhen
of North America.

00:55:39.270 --> 00:55:41.860
Every screen here was assembled
in Tijuana.

00:55:41.860 --> 00:55:45.130
The Samsungs and the Sonys have
massive plants there in

00:55:45.130 --> 00:55:47.340
the special economic zone.

00:55:47.340 --> 00:55:49.210
Mexico graduates more engineers
than the United

00:55:49.210 --> 00:55:52.370
States, 55,000 a year.

00:55:52.370 --> 00:55:56.490
We are outside of the export
control zone in Tijuana.

00:55:56.490 --> 00:56:00.650
We have access to ISO 6000,
9000, engineers and operations

00:56:00.650 --> 00:56:04.255
managers who we could never find
or afford in San Diego.

00:56:06.910 --> 00:56:08.580
Now I'm a maquiladora.

00:56:08.580 --> 00:56:11.450
I'm a Mexican, high-tech
entrepreneur.

00:56:11.450 --> 00:56:13.060
How did this happen?

00:56:13.060 --> 00:56:14.680
But the answer is Jordi.

00:56:14.680 --> 00:56:17.310
He taught me everything about
the stuff that really

00:56:17.310 --> 00:56:20.670
mattered, which was how do you
bring manufacturing back to

00:56:20.670 --> 00:56:21.130
North America.

00:56:21.130 --> 00:56:23.070
How do you do high-tech,
but built on the

00:56:23.070 --> 00:56:24.320
web's innovation model?

00:56:24.320 --> 00:56:26.840
How do you compete with the
aerospace industry with a

00:56:26.840 --> 00:56:29.430
bottoms-up, home brew computing
club model?

00:56:29.430 --> 00:56:31.220
It turns out he knew that.

00:56:31.220 --> 00:56:33.040
I didn't know I needed
to know that.

00:56:33.040 --> 00:56:34.280
But he just knew that.

00:56:34.280 --> 00:56:36.730
And because he'd proven himself
in the community, he

00:56:36.730 --> 00:56:38.600
was the right person
to do it with.

00:56:38.600 --> 00:56:41.670
So there's the answer
to Joy's paradox.

00:56:41.670 --> 00:56:43.450
You don't find people, the
right people, on the web.

00:56:43.450 --> 00:56:44.590
They find you.

00:56:44.590 --> 00:56:45.620
You put your idea out there.

00:56:45.620 --> 00:56:47.260
You start something.

00:56:47.260 --> 00:56:48.520
You share your ideas.

00:56:48.520 --> 00:56:50.130
And the smartest people
in the world will find

00:56:50.130 --> 00:56:51.520
you for their reasons.

00:56:51.520 --> 00:56:56.520
And ultimately, they turn out
to be the secret to this new

00:56:56.520 --> 00:56:58.430
industrial model.

00:56:58.430 --> 00:57:03.100
So with that, this is all
described and much more with

00:57:03.100 --> 00:57:06.110
many other examples in the book
that came out last week.

00:57:06.110 --> 00:57:07.290
But thank you, very much.

00:57:07.290 --> 00:57:08.547
I'll take your questions.

