01:03:31.800 --> 01:03:32.070
CHRIS ANDERSON: Yes.

01:03:32.070 --> 01:03:32.530
Exactly.

01:03:32.530 --> 01:03:36.226
MALE SPEAKER: And you alluded
to that with the 3D--

01:03:36.226 --> 01:03:38.130
CHRIS ANDERSON: 123 CAD--
the 3D [INAUDIBLE]

01:03:38.130 --> 01:03:40.170
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah, the 3D
scanner thing and then some of

01:03:40.170 --> 01:03:40.630
the software.

01:03:40.630 --> 01:03:45.730
But I was wondering what's
remaining for

01:03:45.730 --> 01:03:47.240
it to really become--

01:03:47.240 --> 01:03:50.200
where do you see that analogy
playing out where we all have

01:03:50.200 --> 01:03:52.550
good enough software that prints
posters and prints

01:03:52.550 --> 01:03:54.230
stuff for us, that we don't
think about it.

01:03:54.230 --> 01:03:54.840
CHRIS ANDERSON: That's
a great question.

01:03:54.840 --> 01:03:56.900
It's a really interesting
information problem.

01:03:56.900 --> 01:03:59.540
So right now, what it does is,
right now, the wizards will

01:03:59.540 --> 01:04:02.120
walk you through a relatively
simple process, which is,

01:04:02.120 --> 01:04:04.420
basically, do you want to output
it on a 3D printer?

01:04:04.420 --> 01:04:06.480
Or do you want to output
it in 2D in layers?

01:04:06.480 --> 01:04:08.110
So you start there.

01:04:08.110 --> 01:04:09.740
Then they walk you through
some material choices.

01:04:09.740 --> 01:04:13.730
And this is based on both
structural considerations and

01:04:13.730 --> 01:04:14.730
cost considerations.

01:04:14.730 --> 01:04:18.190
Does he want it to be wood, or
cardboard, or plastic, or

01:04:18.190 --> 01:04:20.780
metal, or glass, or whatever?

01:04:20.780 --> 01:04:23.100
Then they walk you through some
volume-- you can make the

01:04:23.100 --> 01:04:26.730
model a little simpler, remove
some internal surfaces and

01:04:26.730 --> 01:04:28.780
reduce the cost and weight
and things like that.

01:04:28.780 --> 01:04:33.230
So that's kind of where
they're at right now.

01:04:33.230 --> 01:04:36.880
Now, when you go to high-end
CAD, then the CAD program

01:04:36.880 --> 01:04:39.770
itself is able to do things like
complex fluid dynamics

01:04:39.770 --> 01:04:41.820
and finite element analysis.

01:04:41.820 --> 01:04:43.560
And they go through the physics
of the materials

01:04:43.560 --> 01:04:44.340
themselves.

01:04:44.340 --> 01:04:46.480
And they'll start to do
things like, well,

01:04:46.480 --> 01:04:48.210
this wall is too thick.

01:04:48.210 --> 01:04:49.040
It doesn't need to
be that thick.

01:04:49.040 --> 01:04:51.190
And this wall is too thin.

01:04:51.190 --> 01:04:53.850
Here's a flex point which
needs to be bolstered.

01:04:53.850 --> 01:04:56.210
You might want to pick a
different material here, given

01:04:56.210 --> 01:04:58.020
the strength considerations,
weight

01:04:58.020 --> 01:04:59.320
considerations, things like that.

01:04:59.320 --> 01:05:00.380
That's high-end stuff.

01:05:00.380 --> 01:05:04.890
But it's increasingly within
a plug-in on some

01:05:04.890 --> 01:05:05.770
of these free tools.

01:05:05.770 --> 01:05:10.810
You can download CFD or finite
element analysis tools.

01:05:10.810 --> 01:05:12.970
And then you'd move to the next
level, which is, let's

01:05:12.970 --> 01:05:15.310
say you want to injection
mold something.

01:05:15.310 --> 01:05:18.210
So it's very easy to
3D print your part.

01:05:18.210 --> 01:05:19.120
You've got your prototype.

01:05:19.120 --> 01:05:20.970
Then take the inverse
and CNC it.

01:05:20.970 --> 01:05:22.160
Now you've got your mold.

01:05:22.160 --> 01:05:25.200
OK, that's great, except for,
actually flowing plastic into

01:05:25.200 --> 01:05:28.230
a mold is not trivial.

01:05:28.230 --> 01:05:29.080
It's easy to put it in.

01:05:29.080 --> 01:05:32.240
But the problem is that
plastic shrinks.

01:05:32.240 --> 01:05:33.720
It basically goes
into one place.

01:05:33.720 --> 01:05:36.400
And you want the shrinkage
to avoid distortion.

01:05:36.400 --> 01:05:40.820
So guys who have been doing this
forever know exactly how

01:05:40.820 --> 01:05:43.910
to design a mold so the plastic
flows perfectly and

01:05:43.910 --> 01:05:48.100
then shrinks at an even rate
and you get high yield.

01:05:48.100 --> 01:05:50.540
Right now, that's basically--

01:05:50.540 --> 01:05:52.690
smart people have been
doing it forever.

01:05:52.690 --> 01:05:54.890
But there's no reason why
it can't be software.

01:05:54.890 --> 01:05:56.290
And I'm sure, if you have
enough money, there is

01:05:56.290 --> 01:05:57.760
software out there that
does it right now.

01:05:57.760 --> 01:05:59.730
But there's still an element
of craftsmanship that's in

01:05:59.730 --> 01:06:00.688
manufacturing.

01:06:00.688 --> 01:06:02.640
MALE SPEAKER: Thank you.

01:06:02.640 --> 01:06:02.966
FEMALE SPEAKER: Hi.

01:06:02.966 --> 01:06:06.300
I have a question as to how
accessible you think this

01:06:06.300 --> 01:06:08.640
revolution really is, when we're
talking about people who

01:06:08.640 --> 01:06:11.750
might not even have internet
connections, who don't have

01:06:11.750 --> 01:06:15.770
$1,000 or more to buy a
MakerBot, and whether this

01:06:15.770 --> 01:06:18.250
revolution may just exacerbate
the effects

01:06:18.250 --> 01:06:19.585
of the digital divide.

01:06:19.585 --> 01:06:21.360
CHRIS ANDERSON: Well, it's
certainly a lot more

01:06:21.360 --> 01:06:23.400
accessible than it ever
has been before.

01:06:23.400 --> 01:06:25.880
So one of the things that Neil
Gershenfeld at the MIT Media

01:06:25.880 --> 01:06:29.670
Lab, or now, actually, the
Center for Atoms and Bits, did

01:06:29.670 --> 01:06:33.610
with his Fab Labs was
specifically target Africa and

01:06:33.610 --> 01:06:35.500
other places that didn't
have access.

01:06:35.500 --> 01:06:37.720
It's largely because these are
people who really don't--

01:06:37.720 --> 01:06:41.480
we have access to highly
manufactured quality parts,

01:06:41.480 --> 01:06:42.990
because we have Walmarts
and all that.

01:06:42.990 --> 01:06:43.820
They typically don't.

01:06:43.820 --> 01:06:46.920
And so there's a notion of
self-empowerment in that.

01:06:46.920 --> 01:06:49.000
Obviously, you have problems
like the technology is still

01:06:49.000 --> 01:06:50.870
relatively expensive, you need
electricity, internet

01:06:50.870 --> 01:06:52.360
connection is good, et cetera.

01:06:55.270 --> 01:06:58.670
I think, electricity is kind of
a necessary element still.

01:06:58.670 --> 01:07:02.990
But putting that aside,
let's just start with

01:07:02.990 --> 01:07:04.650
the barriers to entry.

01:07:04.650 --> 01:07:06.435
The barrier to entry
used to be you

01:07:06.435 --> 01:07:07.170
needed machining skills.

01:07:07.170 --> 01:07:07.850
You don't need that any more.

01:07:07.850 --> 01:07:09.560
Then the barrier tended to
be you need this machine.

01:07:09.560 --> 01:07:11.790
And now you can either afford
the machine, or you can have

01:07:11.790 --> 01:07:13.220
access to it via a service.

01:07:13.220 --> 01:07:14.650
Then the barrier to
entry was CAD.

01:07:14.650 --> 01:07:17.010
CAD was super hard.

01:07:17.010 --> 01:07:20.360
Check out Tinkercad, which is
a web-based CAD program.

01:07:20.360 --> 01:07:23.190
It looks very toy-like and
game-like on the surface.

01:07:23.190 --> 01:07:24.960
But underneath, actually,
it's run by a

01:07:24.960 --> 01:07:26.600
former Google engineer.

01:07:26.600 --> 01:07:27.620
FEMALE SPEAKER: It it free?

01:07:27.620 --> 01:07:27.875
CHRIS ANDERSON: Sorry?

01:07:27.875 --> 01:07:28.460
FEMALE SPEAKER: Is it free?

01:07:28.460 --> 01:07:30.140
CHRIS ANDERSON: Absolutely
free.

01:07:30.140 --> 01:07:30.790
Absolutely.

01:07:30.790 --> 01:07:32.550
That's the point.

01:07:32.550 --> 01:07:33.780
It's the web.

01:07:33.780 --> 01:07:35.120
I wrote a book on
that as well.

01:07:35.120 --> 01:07:38.010
[LAUGHTER]

01:07:38.010 --> 01:07:39.300
CHRIS ANDERSON: But underneath,
it's got a very

01:07:39.300 --> 01:07:45.450
powerful engine, basically a
polygon construction engine.

01:07:47.950 --> 01:07:51.360
A lot of the arcane
language of CAD is

01:07:51.360 --> 01:07:52.980
abstracted away in that.

01:07:52.980 --> 01:07:55.530
And then, finally, Minecraft.

01:07:55.530 --> 01:07:58.470
You don't think of Minecraft as
a CAD program, but it is.

01:07:58.470 --> 01:08:00.440
And so I think the kids
really grab--

01:08:00.440 --> 01:08:02.720
kids really understand 3D
spaces and polygons and

01:08:02.720 --> 01:08:04.870
navigating these screen
environments.

01:08:04.870 --> 01:08:07.930
And if you can navigate
Minecraft, you can basically

01:08:07.930 --> 01:08:09.840
navigate a CAD environment.

01:08:09.840 --> 01:08:13.540
And LEGO Digital Designer is
a good example of that.

01:08:13.540 --> 01:08:15.820
One of the nice things about
LEGO is that is a smart

01:08:15.820 --> 01:08:18.580
material in that the pieces know
how they fit together.

01:08:18.580 --> 01:08:20.600
You can't put them
together wrong.

01:08:20.600 --> 01:08:22.910
They snap into alignment.

01:08:22.910 --> 01:08:27.200
And what LEGO Digital Designer
is, is CAD for LEGO.

01:08:27.200 --> 01:08:30.490
But it allows you to create
relatively complex objects.

01:08:30.490 --> 01:08:31.700
And kids are great at that.

01:08:31.700 --> 01:08:33.790
So I think that a lot of the
intellectual barriers to entry

01:08:33.790 --> 01:08:34.729
are falling.

01:08:34.729 --> 01:08:36.130
I mean, obviously, you still
need a little money.

01:08:36.130 --> 01:08:37.770
And you need electricity,
et cetera.

01:08:37.770 --> 01:08:41.180
But the point is you can take
any computer lab today, add

01:08:41.180 --> 01:08:43.729
two 3D printers, and now
it's a design lab.

01:08:43.729 --> 01:08:45.540
And we have computer labs.

01:08:45.540 --> 01:08:47.069
And we have art classes.

01:08:47.069 --> 01:08:48.960
And the two don't
meet each other.

01:08:48.960 --> 01:08:51.310
And yet, you put two to three
3D printers in the computer

01:08:51.310 --> 01:08:54.399
lab, and now you've got that
synthesis of the two.

01:08:54.399 --> 01:08:59.500
And you're not just making a
finger painting to bring home.

01:08:59.500 --> 01:09:02.660
You're actually taking your
ideas and making them real and

01:09:02.660 --> 01:09:05.010
learning skills that are
basically 21st century

01:09:05.010 --> 01:09:05.670
competencies.

01:09:05.670 --> 01:09:09.460
So I think that that's the real
exciting thing here is

01:09:09.460 --> 01:09:13.490
that this is now, if it's easy
enough for kids to use, it's

01:09:13.490 --> 01:09:14.840
easy enough for everybody
to use.

01:09:14.840 --> 01:09:17.229
And fundamentally, growing up
knowing that you can make your

01:09:17.229 --> 01:09:20.370
ideas real is going to create
the generation of innovators

01:09:20.370 --> 01:09:22.310
that are going to drive the next
Industrial Revolution.

01:09:22.310 --> 01:09:23.100
FEMALE SPEAKER: Thank you.

01:09:23.100 --> 01:09:24.819
Really quick follow-up
question.

01:09:24.819 --> 01:09:27.250
You alluded to your children
earlier on.

01:09:27.250 --> 01:09:29.330
What was actually their
level of involvement?

01:09:29.330 --> 01:09:33.620
I assume that they weren't the
ones drawing CAD diagrams or

01:09:33.620 --> 01:09:34.994
anything like that.

01:09:34.994 --> 01:09:39.560
CHRIS ANDERSON: So it's
a bit of a sore point.

01:09:39.560 --> 01:09:44.100
Their level of involvement is
always they're very happy to

01:09:44.100 --> 01:09:46.460
try something once with me.

01:09:46.460 --> 01:09:50.399
But if it's hard, they lose
interest pretty quickly.

01:09:50.399 --> 01:09:53.210
They love LEGO Digital Designer,
because they just

01:09:53.210 --> 01:09:54.000
want play on screens.

01:09:54.000 --> 01:09:55.460
And it's one thing we'll
let them do.

01:09:55.460 --> 01:09:58.130
We won't let them play video
games all the time.

01:09:58.130 --> 01:10:00.830
They tend not to
use CAD a lot.

01:10:00.830 --> 01:10:02.560
Instead, what they do is they
download files from

01:10:02.560 --> 01:10:03.943
Thingiverse and then
just modify them.

01:10:03.943 --> 01:10:04.790
FEMALE SPEAKER: OK.

01:10:04.790 --> 01:10:07.820
CHRIS ANDERSON: But given a
choice between anything on a

01:10:07.820 --> 01:10:10.730
screen and not on a screen,
they'll do anything on a

01:10:10.730 --> 01:10:11.370
screen if we'd let them.

01:10:11.370 --> 01:10:13.340
So we call this educational.

01:10:13.340 --> 01:10:15.080
And they'll do it.

01:10:15.080 --> 01:10:15.800
FEMALE SPEAKER: OK.

01:10:15.800 --> 01:10:16.520
Thanks.

01:10:16.520 --> 01:10:17.660
MALE SPEAKER: Thanks a lot.

01:10:17.660 --> 01:10:18.970
This was really, really
informative.

01:10:18.970 --> 01:10:20.870
A couple of points, I guess.

01:10:20.870 --> 01:10:23.070
One was an open question, which
is that, previously,

01:10:23.070 --> 01:10:26.440
when you wanted to control
dangerous objects or drones

01:10:26.440 --> 01:10:29.190
and so on, you had export
control norms and so on.

01:10:29.190 --> 01:10:30.650
And now you're ending up in a
world where you've got to

01:10:30.650 --> 01:10:34.510
control sale of machines that
could do anything from produce

01:10:34.510 --> 01:10:37.140
really helpful houses to drones,
which could be loaded

01:10:37.140 --> 01:10:37.840
with explosives.

01:10:37.840 --> 01:10:40.970
And there's a big risk to how
do you moderate and control

01:10:40.970 --> 01:10:43.100
this, at the same time,
keep the open model?

01:10:43.100 --> 01:10:44.615
So one is what's your
thoughts on that?

01:10:44.615 --> 01:10:46.600
CHRIS ANDERSON: So as you might
imagine, I get this

01:10:46.600 --> 01:10:47.180
question a lot.

01:10:47.180 --> 01:10:48.370
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah, I'm sure.

01:10:48.370 --> 01:10:49.630
CHRIS ANDERSON: Open sourcing
drones, what

01:10:49.630 --> 01:10:52.120
could possibly go wrong?

01:10:52.120 --> 01:10:54.780
So the simple answer is that--
of course, this is true for

01:10:54.780 --> 01:10:55.730
any technology.

01:10:55.730 --> 01:10:59.080
You can misuse computers
as well.

01:10:59.080 --> 01:11:01.750
We feel that we have an
obligation to do two things.

01:11:01.750 --> 01:11:04.240
One is to promote best
practice, to promote

01:11:04.240 --> 01:11:06.390
responsible use.

01:11:06.390 --> 01:11:10.790
For example, you're not allowed
to fly drones in the

01:11:10.790 --> 01:11:13.150
US National airspace for
commercial purposes.

01:11:13.150 --> 01:11:15.300
But you can fly it
recreationally, as long as you

01:11:15.300 --> 01:11:19.040
stay below 400 feet and within
visual line of sight, so that

01:11:19.040 --> 01:11:21.370
you can provide that [? sense ?]
and be able to

01:11:21.370 --> 01:11:22.620
stay out of the way of
[? mandated ?] aviation.

01:11:27.890 --> 01:11:30.150
We know our technology can
fly beyond line of sight.

01:11:30.150 --> 01:11:32.120
We know it can fly
above 400 feet.

01:11:32.120 --> 01:11:34.650
We are hard core about
discouraging that.

01:11:34.650 --> 01:11:37.750
Anybody posts a video doing
that, we come down on them.

01:11:37.750 --> 01:11:42.130
We just bang on all the time
about safety and responsible

01:11:42.130 --> 01:11:44.390
use and about the
FAA guidelines.

01:11:44.390 --> 01:11:45.030
So that's one thing.

01:11:45.030 --> 01:11:50.420
The second thing is that we
don't feel we're competent to

01:11:50.420 --> 01:11:52.020
regulate or police this.

01:11:52.020 --> 01:11:55.370
We think it's our obligation to
inform the regulators and

01:11:55.370 --> 01:11:56.710
law enforcement agencies
about what's

01:11:56.710 --> 01:11:58.270
possible and what's happening.

01:11:58.270 --> 01:12:01.420
So what we do is we reach out to
the agencies out there and

01:12:01.420 --> 01:12:02.330
we invite them in.

01:12:02.330 --> 01:12:04.040
We tell our community
we invite them in.

01:12:04.040 --> 01:12:06.200
I get a quarterly check
up with the FBI.

01:12:06.200 --> 01:12:07.160
We're like, hey,
how's it going?

01:12:07.160 --> 01:12:09.190
Everything's going fine.

01:12:09.190 --> 01:12:12.960
And we say, if anybody starts
talking about something

01:12:12.960 --> 01:12:18.450
dangerous, we will ping our
friends in the FBI ASAP.

01:12:18.450 --> 01:12:21.780
If the FBI sees something that's
dangerous, we will--

01:12:21.780 --> 01:12:22.950
and we disclose this.

01:12:22.950 --> 01:12:23.840
We actually don't have
any information.

01:12:23.840 --> 01:12:24.770
All we have is their
email address.

01:12:24.770 --> 01:12:27.790
But we will disclose
the email address.

01:12:27.790 --> 01:12:30.380
And I fly to Washington every
now and then to tell everybody

01:12:30.380 --> 01:12:33.430
what's possible, so that the
people who we've entrusted to

01:12:33.430 --> 01:12:36.170
protect us are informed
about what's possible.

01:12:36.170 --> 01:12:39.490
And we're really transparent
about this with the community.

01:12:39.490 --> 01:12:41.480
If somebody messes this up,
if somebody does something

01:12:41.480 --> 01:12:43.060
dangerous, this is going to
be bad for everybody.

01:12:43.060 --> 01:12:43.930
MALE SPEAKER: Yep.

01:12:43.930 --> 01:12:47.510
CHRIS ANDERSON: And we're just
like, do it, do it in public.

01:12:51.010 --> 01:12:52.760
We as a community have a
responsibility, if we see

01:12:52.760 --> 01:12:55.330
something that we think is
dangerous or irresponsible, to

01:12:55.330 --> 01:12:56.710
tell people about it.

01:12:56.710 --> 01:12:58.910
But we don't feel that we can be
the ones who ultimately are

01:12:58.910 --> 01:12:59.580
the police.

01:12:59.580 --> 01:13:01.650
We're not going to restrict
the technology we release.

01:13:01.650 --> 01:13:06.220
We're just going to inform the
responsible parties about

01:13:06.220 --> 01:13:07.890
what's being released and about
what's been done so that

01:13:07.890 --> 01:13:09.460
they can do the job.

01:13:09.460 --> 01:13:11.280
MALE SPEAKER: The other
follow-up questions that are

01:13:11.280 --> 01:13:14.390
related, but not connected, is
that, as you think about spare

01:13:14.390 --> 01:13:16.090
parts as the entire change
that's going to happen over

01:13:16.090 --> 01:13:21.150
the next 5, 10 or 15 years
of how production and

01:13:21.150 --> 01:13:26.000
mass-customization is going to
happen, where do you see

01:13:26.000 --> 01:13:27.470
people evolving in
their skill sets?

01:13:27.470 --> 01:13:30.070
Because I think, for people who
grew up with CAD software,

01:13:30.070 --> 01:13:30.960
or if they're engineers,
it's easy.

01:13:30.960 --> 01:13:34.460
But for the rest of them,
they're away from that realm

01:13:34.460 --> 01:13:34.885
of learning.

01:13:34.885 --> 01:13:35.550
CHRIS ANDERSON: Yeah.

01:13:35.550 --> 01:13:37.680
Well, I think, in the same way
that you don't think that

01:13:37.680 --> 01:13:40.840
you're publishing when you
post to Facebook, I don't

01:13:40.840 --> 01:13:45.380
think you're going to think
you're doing CAD when you do

01:13:45.380 --> 01:13:48.930
reality capture of some object
and then make it cooler.

01:13:48.930 --> 01:13:53.280
I think that, basically, the
opportunity is to abstract the

01:13:53.280 --> 01:13:55.670
complexity and the professional
standards out of

01:13:55.670 --> 01:13:58.410
this and just come up with a
new design interface, a new

01:13:58.410 --> 01:14:00.350
design language that
allows people to

01:14:00.350 --> 01:14:01.850
express themselves naturally.

01:14:01.850 --> 01:14:03.490
MALE SPEAKER: And this is
for everyone else here.

01:14:03.490 --> 01:14:05.790
As Googlers, there is the
Garage, which is our shared

01:14:05.790 --> 01:14:07.860
working space, which also has
access to a 3D printer.

01:14:07.860 --> 01:14:09.360
Which I found out about
today, morning.

01:14:09.360 --> 01:14:09.900
CHRIS ANDERSON: Excellent.

01:14:09.900 --> 01:14:11.270
Thank you.

01:14:11.270 --> 01:14:12.890
MALE SPEAKER: Thank you
for coming to speak.

01:14:12.890 --> 01:14:15.060
You just talked about the
Open Hardware Movement.

01:14:15.060 --> 01:14:16.620
And you mentioned
MakerBot a lot.

01:14:16.620 --> 01:14:19.440
And I'm sure you're aware that
they seem to have backpedalled

01:14:19.440 --> 01:14:21.780
slightly on the Open
Hardware Movement.

01:14:21.780 --> 01:14:27.720
And also some concern over the
language in Thingiverse's

01:14:27.720 --> 01:14:30.080
agreements, to what you're
giving to them when you upload

01:14:30.080 --> 01:14:30.960
your models.

01:14:30.960 --> 01:14:33.300
Is that paranoia on the
community's part that

01:14:33.300 --> 01:14:34.240
something's happening there?

01:14:34.240 --> 01:14:35.120
Or is there something afoot?

01:14:35.120 --> 01:14:36.760
And what does that mean for
the future of the Open

01:14:36.760 --> 01:14:37.690
Hardware Movement?

01:14:37.690 --> 01:14:38.480
CHRIS ANDERSON: Great
question.

01:14:38.480 --> 01:14:39.620
Thank you, for raising that.

01:14:39.620 --> 01:14:42.680
The answer is a little
bit of both.

01:14:42.680 --> 01:14:45.410
So just the facts, for those
of you who aren't

01:14:45.410 --> 01:14:46.480
familiar with this.

01:14:46.480 --> 01:14:49.850
MakerBot is built on the RepRap
platform, which is an

01:14:49.850 --> 01:14:53.930
open-source hardware and
software platform.

01:14:53.930 --> 01:14:57.840
MakerBot was 100% open and, in
this latest version, had the

01:14:57.840 --> 01:14:59.090
Replicator 2.

01:15:01.240 --> 01:15:03.020
Just to put the facts on the
table, the biggest problem is

01:15:03.020 --> 01:15:04.870
not that they've closed it.

01:15:04.870 --> 01:15:06.560
The biggest problem is they
didn't say what they were

01:15:06.560 --> 01:15:07.830
doing on Day One.

01:15:07.830 --> 01:15:08.840
And so there was
some ambiguity.

01:15:08.840 --> 01:15:11.210
And people suspected
the worst.

01:15:11.210 --> 01:15:12.740
What they are actually doing--

01:15:12.740 --> 01:15:13.990
oh, and by the way, the
Thingiverse thing was a

01:15:13.990 --> 01:15:14.870
complete misunderstanding.

01:15:14.870 --> 01:15:17.120
Those Terms of Service were in
place for a year already.

01:15:17.120 --> 01:15:19.970
And that was just paranoia.

01:15:19.970 --> 01:15:23.760
But here's what's actually
happening is that they've

01:15:23.760 --> 01:15:27.700
looked at the product and they
said, what about this is

01:15:27.700 --> 01:15:31.200
usefully open, which is
to say, we get open.

01:15:31.200 --> 01:15:32.850
We understand that, if you give
something back, you get

01:15:32.850 --> 01:15:35.970
more in return and that you
create a platform for which

01:15:35.970 --> 01:15:36.730
innovation can happen.

01:15:36.730 --> 01:15:39.200
But there's certain elements
that are just not really

01:15:39.200 --> 01:15:41.040
practical for people.

01:15:41.040 --> 01:15:43.955
So for example, their enclosure,
which is powder

01:15:43.955 --> 01:15:47.360
coated steel, you need access
to machinery that regular

01:15:47.360 --> 01:15:48.640
people don't have to do that.

01:15:48.640 --> 01:15:50.290
And they didn't feel that that
was really adding a lot of

01:15:50.290 --> 01:15:51.510
value was the enclosure.

01:15:51.510 --> 01:15:54.160
Whereas, the circuit boards,
the electronics

01:15:54.160 --> 01:15:55.530
themselves, are open.

01:15:55.530 --> 01:15:57.450
They're actually the same ones
that were in the previous one.

01:15:57.450 --> 01:16:01.000
Their software, their underlying
slicing engine,

01:16:01.000 --> 01:16:02.920
which does their
Gcode, is open.

01:16:02.920 --> 01:16:07.970
Their UI is not, on the grounds
that they want to have

01:16:07.970 --> 01:16:08.790
some protection.

01:16:08.790 --> 01:16:10.450
But they felt that the
underlying slicing engine was

01:16:10.450 --> 01:16:13.230
the most useful one
to release.

01:16:13.230 --> 01:16:15.560
So the big problem was they
didn't say that on Day One.

01:16:15.560 --> 01:16:17.310
And so people freaked out.

01:16:19.970 --> 01:16:22.610
So where they ended up is what
we call a hybrid model, which

01:16:22.610 --> 01:16:25.580
is you open what you think is
most useful and really serves

01:16:25.580 --> 01:16:26.290
the community best.

01:16:26.290 --> 01:16:31.310
And you close just enough to
give yourself a competitive

01:16:31.310 --> 01:16:33.620
advantage, so that you can build
a sustainable business.

01:16:33.620 --> 01:16:36.300
And I think they got it right.

01:16:36.300 --> 01:16:37.740
I'm not going to say they
got it 100% right.

01:16:37.740 --> 01:16:39.380
But I think that a hybrid
model is probably the

01:16:39.380 --> 01:16:39.830
right way to go.

01:16:39.830 --> 01:16:43.620
So for example, on our drones,
our hardware is 100% open.

01:16:43.620 --> 01:16:44.880
We release the [INAUDIBLE]
files.

01:16:44.880 --> 01:16:48.710
Our software is 100%
open, GPL'd.

01:16:48.710 --> 01:16:51.080
When we had laser cut stuff,
we released all those

01:16:51.080 --> 01:16:51.870
as laser cut files.

01:16:51.870 --> 01:16:54.910
We now have injection molded
arms when the designs are in

01:16:54.910 --> 01:16:55.940
SolidWorks.

01:16:55.940 --> 01:16:57.550
And we actually release the
dimensional drawings.

01:16:57.550 --> 01:17:00.980
But we don't release the
SolidWorks files, because

01:17:00.980 --> 01:17:02.730
you'd need an injection
molding machine and

01:17:02.730 --> 01:17:04.940
SolidWorks, which costs
$5,000, to use this.

01:17:04.940 --> 01:17:07.420
And we didn't feel that that
was adding a huge amount of

01:17:07.420 --> 01:17:09.320
value, when we also
are constantly

01:17:09.320 --> 01:17:12.260
ripped off by the Chinese.

01:17:12.260 --> 01:17:14.475
Our license allows you
to use our stuff and

01:17:14.475 --> 01:17:14.960
compete against us.

01:17:14.960 --> 01:17:18.900
But it doesn't allow you to
violate our trademark and not

01:17:18.900 --> 01:17:21.620
adhere to the terms
of the license.

01:17:21.620 --> 01:17:24.490
So we're like, you know what,
these injection molder arms

01:17:24.490 --> 01:17:25.470
are just going to make
it easier for the

01:17:25.470 --> 01:17:26.560
cloners to rip us off.

01:17:26.560 --> 01:17:28.110
And they're not adding a lot
of value to the community.

01:17:28.110 --> 01:17:30.250
So that's where we drew
the line right there.

01:17:30.250 --> 01:17:32.790
Now I'm sure there's someone
out there who thinks we're

01:17:32.790 --> 01:17:35.400
betraying the cause and
we've violated the

01:17:35.400 --> 01:17:36.490
ethic of open hardware.

01:17:36.490 --> 01:17:40.450
But we feel that we made a
reasonable decision to build a

01:17:40.450 --> 01:17:42.740
sustainable business.

01:17:42.740 --> 01:17:45.540
And the truth is, actually,
nobody has complained.

01:17:45.540 --> 01:17:47.193
Maybe they will now that
I've mentioned it.

01:17:47.193 --> 01:17:47.576
[LAUGHTER]

01:17:47.576 --> 01:17:48.370
CHRIS ANDERSON: But
so far, so good.

01:17:48.370 --> 01:17:50.410
So I think that we're all
kind of navigating--

01:17:50.410 --> 01:17:51.310
so I talk to [? Bria ?]

01:17:51.310 --> 01:17:51.780
from [? Maker ?]

01:17:51.780 --> 01:17:52.310
a lot about it.

01:17:52.310 --> 01:17:56.670
So we're all finding our way
towards being mostly--

01:17:56.670 --> 01:17:58.860
Raspberry Pi, for example,
is not open hardware.

01:17:58.860 --> 01:18:00.230
They're open software.

01:18:00.230 --> 01:18:02.850
And I think we had a good post
on Wired Design the other day

01:18:02.850 --> 01:18:05.585
where a designer said, you've
got to sell out a little to

01:18:05.585 --> 01:18:06.410
sell a lot.

01:18:06.410 --> 01:18:08.920
Now that's not exactly the way
I would have phrased it.

01:18:08.920 --> 01:18:15.590
But the point is is that we
didn't join a priesthood here.

01:18:15.590 --> 01:18:18.220
We believe in open source
because it works.

01:18:18.220 --> 01:18:18.830
We've done it.

01:18:18.830 --> 01:18:20.460
We've got years of experience
in this.

01:18:20.460 --> 01:18:22.360
We do it because it's a
practical way to build

01:18:22.360 --> 01:18:23.180
innovation communities.

01:18:23.180 --> 01:18:26.680
But we're not going to be
doctrinaire about it.

01:18:26.680 --> 01:18:29.020
We're going to get the balance
right, so that we can serve

01:18:29.020 --> 01:18:32.500
both our community and our
customers and, to be frank,

01:18:32.500 --> 01:18:34.400
our investors, because
these are big

01:18:34.400 --> 01:18:36.880
businesses now, at best.

01:18:36.880 --> 01:18:40.140
And that involves being flexible
and evolving the

01:18:40.140 --> 01:18:41.040
model as you go.

01:18:41.040 --> 01:18:41.610
MALE SPEAKER: All right.

01:18:41.610 --> 01:18:42.398
Thank you.

01:18:42.398 --> 01:18:43.892
CHRIS ANDERSON: Thank you.

01:18:43.892 --> 01:18:46.390
MALE SPEAKER: There's been
some rumblings about 3D

01:18:46.390 --> 01:18:48.380
printing on a much larger scale,
like people printing

01:18:48.380 --> 01:18:49.380
the walls to houses.

01:18:49.380 --> 01:18:49.850
CHRIS ANDERSON: Yeah.

01:18:49.850 --> 01:18:51.340
MALE SPEAKER: What do you think
is the timeline for that

01:18:51.340 --> 01:18:52.810
becoming more mainstream.

01:18:52.810 --> 01:18:54.710
And when can I print
out an apartment?

01:18:54.710 --> 01:18:55.280
CHRIS ANDERSON: Good question.

01:18:55.280 --> 01:18:56.720
So that is already possible.

01:18:56.720 --> 01:18:58.330
There's already some demos.

01:18:58.330 --> 01:19:00.680
I'm using poured concrete
and basically big heads.

01:19:00.680 --> 01:19:02.840
Now there's one really
interesting demo.

01:19:02.840 --> 01:19:06.800
One of the problems with the
house scale 3D printers which

01:19:06.800 --> 01:19:08.880
pours it, you actually have to
build a 3D printer as big as a

01:19:08.880 --> 01:19:11.610
house, or slightly
bigger, actually.

01:19:11.610 --> 01:19:14.740
There's some really cool
demos involving

01:19:14.740 --> 01:19:17.430
stringing wires from trees.

01:19:17.430 --> 01:19:20.740
You basically just need three
points like a hammock, minus

01:19:20.740 --> 01:19:21.680
one point, [LAUGHS]

01:19:21.680 --> 01:19:22.800
I guess.

01:19:22.800 --> 01:19:24.640
So you just string
wires from trees,

01:19:24.640 --> 01:19:25.990
cables of various sorts.

01:19:25.990 --> 01:19:28.690
And then you just
calibrate it.

01:19:28.690 --> 01:19:30.930
And then you let the head
move on these wires.

01:19:30.930 --> 01:19:32.650
And they have a three
dimensional axis.

01:19:32.650 --> 01:19:36.760
And you've basically created an
in situ, ad hoc, one off 3D

01:19:36.760 --> 01:19:38.420
printer for houses.

01:19:38.420 --> 01:19:41.430
Now this is definitely
experimental lab stuff.

01:19:41.430 --> 01:19:45.190
I wouldn't guarantee the
resolution of a 3D printer

01:19:45.190 --> 01:19:47.950
locked to a tree, which can
slightly bend a little bit.

01:19:47.950 --> 01:19:49.840
But you can kind of see
where this is going.

01:19:49.840 --> 01:19:52.760
And originally they were doing
it as an experiment in

01:19:52.760 --> 01:19:56.170
building, in making concrete
shapes that would be too hard

01:19:56.170 --> 01:19:59.895
to make through traditional
casting or pouring techniques.

01:19:59.895 --> 01:20:03.240
So this is kind of an
art thing right now.

01:20:03.240 --> 01:20:04.830
And don't forget, you also have
to put in things like

01:20:04.830 --> 01:20:06.520
rebar, et cetera.

01:20:06.520 --> 01:20:07.770
So there is that.

01:20:12.390 --> 01:20:13.770
I can't give you a timeline.

01:20:13.770 --> 01:20:15.790
I've seen it work in Italy.

01:20:15.790 --> 01:20:19.240
I don't know how commercial it
is at the moment, but I think

01:20:19.240 --> 01:20:22.810
we're talking a matter of
single digit years.

01:20:22.810 --> 01:20:23.656
MALE SPEAKER: Awesome.

01:20:23.656 --> 01:20:24.230
Thank you.

01:20:24.230 --> 01:20:25.954
CHRIS ANDERSON: Thank you.

